<li><I>Economic Report of the President</I> (Washington, D.C.: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1996), pp. 332 and 311.<p>
<li>The U.S. tax system encourages workers to take their pay as untaxed fringe benefits instead of taxable cash wages. Employee non-wage benefits accounted for 41.3 percent of payroll costs in 1993, up from almost 18.7 percent in 1951 and 36.6 percent in 1979. See U.S. Chamber of Commerce, "Employee Benefits Survey," various years.<p>
<li>Hourly wage data exclude benefits such as health insurance, workers' compensation, and pensions.<p>
