<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin"></center>
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<b>Newt Comes To His Own Defense</b><br>
	Speaker Newt Gingrich came to his own defense in his high-profile ethics controversy over the weekend. It was typical Newtoutspoken, brilliant on certain points, and almost certainly ill-advised. His brash remarks at a town-hall meeting served only to keep the controversy on the front pages. As Rep. Peter King (R., N.Y.)  put it: Gingrich "needs to be smart enough to realize that he's got to end this. He needs to stop talking about what happened and move on." Still, Gingrich was certainly correct to make the following points:<p>

Democrats have thrown dozens of bogus accusations at him, and there should be some penalty for bringing frivolous complaints to the ethics committee.
<p>
The media have been out to get Gingrich, and they have upheld a double standard that lets Democrats get away with anything while Republicans are held to the highest possible ethical scrutiny. 
<p>
But Gingrich is on shakier ground when he defends himself from the charge that he deceived the ethics committee: "I trusted the law firm to have done the job [of advising him] right. They didn't do the job right and I didn't catch them, so I thought the most honorable thing to do when you have done something wrong is to say 'This was a mistake.' " Here is a brief primer to considering the crucial question of whether or not Gingrich lied deliberately: 
<p>
	In Newt's favor is some substantial circumstantial evidence, which has led us to conclude, as we say in our latest issue, that "the distractions of other business, and the absurd multiplicity of the charges brought against him by Democratic hell-hounds, plausibly explain the misinformation he gave Congress."
<p>
	The question, of course, is whether Newt meant to mislead the committee by telling it that GOPAC had nothing to do with the development of his college course. In letters on December 8, 1994 and March 27, 1995 Gingrich said, erroneously, that GOPACcentral to the development of the coursehad nothing to do with it. But in an October 4, 1994 letter Gingrich had admitted that GOPAC was involved in the course. This is fairly compelling evidence that the misstatements in the letters were honest mistakes. 
<p>
	Newt was terribly busytrying to run a revolutionat the time the erroneous letters were sent, and it is reasonable conclude he didn't have time to review them thoroughly, and just trusted his lawyers (after all he was paying them, as he said the other day, to get things right). 
<p>
	It would be monumentally stupid to think he could actually get away with lying to the committee. 
<p>
But there is some evidence the other way, which is why committee counsel James Colein effect, Newt's prosecutor, whose job was to put as harsh a light on Newt as possibleconcluded it reasonable to think Gingrich deliberately lied:
 <p>
	Gingrich had a motive. When he sent the October 4 letter the committee was asking him whether congressional funds had been used to develop the course. At that point, GOPAC's involvement was exculpatory. But the next two letters were focused on tax questions. At this point the involvement of GOPAC, a frankly partisan group, was a liability for Gingrich, and it would have made sense for him to deny that it had anything to do with the course. In other words, denying GOPAC's involvement, if a mistake, was a convenient one. 
<p>
	The letters made several statements that GOPAC had nothing to do with the course. The references would have been hard to missespecially considering they went to the core of the committee's investigationand Gingrich was the only one reviewing them for accuracy. 
<p>
	In September 1996 the ethics committee expanded its inquiry into the question of whether or not Gingrich mislead it. Nonetheless, Gingrich wrote in a letter last October 31 that the letters in question were accurate. As Ethics Committee member Steven Schiff (R., N.M.) said: "One would have thought when we pointed out the letters, he would have read them. And if something was wrong you thought he would bring it to our attention. But he did not. Instead he sends us a letter repeating what he said before. He doesn't see anything wrong. Well, that makes it tough for us to understand that in fact this is as innocent as some people would have us believe." (Schiff, however, seems to say the misstatements were honest errors.) 
<p>
It wasn't until Nov. 13 that Gingrich, testifying under oath before the ethics subcommittee, acknowledged the mistakes, and only after prodding. Cole said: "it was not that he just walked in, recognized everything was inaccurate and explained it right off the bat to the subcommittee. . . . [Gingrich] ultimately didafter questioning and . . . showing him documents and things of that naturedid acknowledge that there were inaccurate" statements. 
<p>
	Stay tunedbecause, unfortunately, the Gingrich controversy isn't finished yet.
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
