<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin"></center>
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<b>White House Lies, Cont.</b><br>
It's just the latest exercise in mendacity from a White House that has mastered it. All along the Clinton Administration has alleged that it didn't know that Webster Hubbell was retained by the Lippo Group in 1994 when he was desperately in need of cash. There is an appearance here that the purpose of the deal was to encourage Hubbell to keep his mouth shut about the Clinton scandals. Hubbell denies it, and the White House had been pleading ignorance. Now it turns out that Clinton advisor Bruce Lindsey was indeed aware of the arrangement back in 1994. Other recent White House lies, as documented in Friday's <I>Washington Post</I>, include the canard that Lippo big-wig James Riady and fund-raiser John Huang visited the White House for "social chats" and that Vice President Al Gore was unaware that the event he attended at a Buddhist temple in the Fall was actually a fund-raiser. The source of both the Hubbell and RiadyHuang deceptions was Lindsey, who seems to be the White House point man on feeding lies to the press; needless to say, he is a very busy man.
<P>
<b>O.J.'s Reality</b><br> 
Take a break for a moment from politics to consider the extraordinary closing arguments in the O. J. Simpson case. O.J.'s lawyers basically maintain that they know the evidence against the football star was tainted, they just don't know how. "The picture that we have," said O.J. lawyer Robert Blasier, who from his wheelchair looked like one of those bizarre Christopher Walken villains from the movies, "is a picture of corruption, of contamination, of planting, tampering, and we don't have all the paint. We're not going to be able to paint you a complete picture of that." Oh, OK. According to the Simpson defense, we live in a strange unaccountable world where things aren't what they seemeven if there is nothing to indicate they are anything different from what they appearand even if no one can say what exactly things are if they aren't what they appear. Got it? The jury gets the case Monday, and hopefully it will strip O.J. of everything he has, including those fancy shoes we never owned. 
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
