<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<b>More DNC Chutzpah</b><br>
Hey, guess what, the Democratic National Committee is no longer going to take contributions from foreign nationals or the American subsidiaries of foreign corporations! Just where are all the Buddhist nuns going to go with their big political donations now? The renewed attempt by the DNC and the White House to get on the side of the angels on campaign finance is just another example of Democratic shamelessness on this topic. The White House has, all along, absurdly maintained that the DNC is some alien entity to which it bears no relation whatsoever. In fact, Bob Woodward reported in his latest book that the White House was essentially directing the production of DNC advertisements (which is illegal, by the way). Asked recently by the <I>Washington Post</I> how the White House could claim such distance from the DNC when it appointed the DNC's top two officials, Gore made a long pausethinking, thinking really hardthen said: "The DNC is a different entity from the campaign, and that's a fact." Uh-huh. We'll believe that as readily as Gore's initial claim that he thought his fund-raiser in a Buddhist temple was really a community outreach project. (He recently had to back down from that misstatement.) 
<P>
The worst part of the Democratic offensive on campaign-finance reform is the push it is giving the McCainFeingold bill. Just finished savaging campaign-finance laws, the Democrats now want to shred the Constitution via this misguided tangle of new election regulations. "It is tough, it is balanced, it is credible," is how Clinton plugged the bill in a recent speech to the DNC. Save us from the talk of new laws, please, until you have an interest in obeying the current ones. 

<P>
<b>Nice Line</b><br>
Says House Majority Whip Tom DeLay: "Everybody's calling for bi-partisanship, but they want us to be bi, while they're partisan." 
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
