<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for January 22, 1997</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Newt: It's Not Over Yet</b><br>
The House Tuesday voted to reprimand and impose a stiff $300,000 penalty on Speaker Newt Gingrich. But this might not be the end to the Gingrich ethics scandal. The newest issue is whether he will pay the fine from personal or campaign funds. If Gingrich were to pay the $300,000 with campaign donations it would be another PR disaster that might again put his speakership in doubt. Notable is the shot House Republican Conference Chairman John Boehner -- who has otherwise been a reliable Gingrich defender -- fired across the Speaker's bow the other day. Even though Gingrich is still undecided on how to pay the fine, Boehner said he should pay it out of personal funds -- an amazing, if subtle, public signal.
	Gingrich needs to be cautious, as independent counsel James Cole's suggestion that he intentionally lied to the Ethics Committee -- and the unprecendented $300,000 penalty -- have rattled  House GOP members' faith in their leader: 
<P>
	Rep. Mark Sanford (R., S.C.) said he feels as though he was "sold down the river" by leaders who pushed him to vote for Gingrich for Speaker before the Ethics Committee report was in. Said Sanford: "There was a uniform chorus within the Republican Conference that said what we're talking about is nothing serious, a speeding ticket. I have yet to see a $300,000 traffic violation." Sanford added, speaking of his children: "I will not say to them, 'I want you to grow up to be like Bill Clinton or Newt Gingrich.' . . . I don't want my son to have to sell his soul for personal power." 
<P>
Said Rep. Jay Dickey (R., Ark.): "I'm having some difficulty placing it in the minor category; $300,000 is a lot of money."
<P>
 Rep. Sue Kelly commented: "For that size a fine, it's a sign that the committee wanted to send a message. I wish we had that information before we had to vote." 
<P>
Rep. Steve Largent (R., Okla.) complained that he felt as though Republicans were misled by their colleagues on the House ethics sub-committee, who wrote a crucial letter before the vote for Speaker saying they knew no reason why they couldn't support Gingrich's election. Asked if he would vote for Gingrich again, Largent replied, "I really don't know the answer to that question. That is why this is such a difficult issue. Is this the guy that should be leading the Republican conference and the House of Representatives? I sure have some reservations, serious reservations."
<P> 
Rep. Tom Coburn said of his vote for Speaker: "I'm sorry that I had to vote at all." (All quotes courtesy of <I>The Hotline</I>, a daily political newsletter.) 
<P>
So far Gingrich has managed to walk a political tightropea plea bargain with the committee, a big assist from Jim McDermottto maintain his grip on the Speakership. The GOP reaction to the Cole report indicates he still has some tough balancing to do, especially when it comes to the question of how he will pay his fine. And, of course, through it all Democrats will continue to bay like wolves for the Speaker's hide. They still might get it.
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
