<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for January 14, 1997</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Libertarianism Pro And Con</b><br>
Two reviews of Charles Murray's new book, <I>What It Means to Be a Libertarian: A Personal Interpretation</I>, appeared Monday, one by Michael Barone in the <I>Wall Street Journal</I> and one by Daniel Casse in the <I>Weekly Standard</I>. Both are thoughtful, incisive writers affiliated with the Right. Barone's review (also of David Boaz's <I>Libertarianism: A Primer</I>) is mostly positive, but raises the question of whether a libertarian polity can defend itself from attacks, both internal and external. A deep and searching question. Casse's review is more critical. It is also, we must say, uncharacteristically disappointing. Too much of Casse's critique of libertarianism is simply that it doesn't poll well. On Social Security and Medicare, he writes, "There is, as the last election proved, no demand to abandon them wholesale outside of libertarian intellectual circles." Americans like paternalism, he argues, citing recent welfare-reform efforts as an example. We'd quibble with that examplepublic pressure may have forced reform, but the power of the welfare bureaucracy and its allies influenced the direction those reforms have taken. But more to the point, the popularity of a program is not relevant to an inquiry into the truth of the philosophy from which that program derives. Casse accepts James Q. Wilson's dictum that government always gets "bigger, more complicated, more burdensome, and more costly." Murray, Casse argues, doesn't confront "this unavoidable truth about government. . . . The sheer magnitude of the problems that government now fumbles with may militate against the voluntary and private solutions that worked during the early part of this country's history." Now in fact libertarians have devoted a lot of attention to this particular argument; a refutation of it is a focus of Richard Epstein's <I>Simple Rules for a Complex World</I> and a muted theme of the conclusion to <I>The Bell Curve</I> (which Murray wrote with the late Richard Herrnstein). Indeed, Barone's review quotes Boaz making the counter-arguments: that increased social complexity makes attempts at government control more and more futile; that complex systemsecological, economic, socialcan be self-ordering. The <I>Weekly Standard</I> seems to have an anti-libertarian streak. We look forward to the day it publishes a cogent critique of libertarian political philosophy. (For an example of one, see Robert P. George's essay in <I>National Review</I>'s 40th anniversary issue.) 
<P>
<b>Cheap Shot</b><br>
In recent weeks, both Robert Novak and the American Conservative Union, led by David Keene, have referred to Laura Ingraham as an "alleged" conservative because she has questioned whether Rep. Dan Burton is the right man to lead the House investigation into Whitewater and related matters. This is childish. Whether or not Ingraham was correctand she is hardly alone in having reservations about Burton's judgmenther conservative credentials are impeccable. One could just as fairly, and just as foolishly, excommunicate Mr. Novak (for his Perotista views on campaign-finance reform) or Mr. Keene (for his years of subservience to Bob Dole).




<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
