<title>Daily Commentary - January 2, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 2, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

When a set of indicators is headed in one direction, while
a related indicator is headed the other way, society must take
notice.  That's the case today in the area of drug-related arrests
among juveniles.  Overall, the national crime rate is declining.
But arrests of young people for drug possession are soaring.
Just one example.  In Fairfax County, Virginia, where I live,
the arrest rate for juvenile drug possession has increased <I>sevenfold</I>
since 1991.

<p>

That number is appalling, not just for what it says about
drug use, but also about the conditions in which drug use thrives.
Police now estimate that there are roughly 25,000 gangs operating
in the United States.  All told, these gangs have 652,000 members.
They typically commit all sorts of crimes, but the drug trade
remains a keystone business for most of them.

<p>

Thomas Constantine, head of the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration, calls this situation &quot;a ticking time bomb.&quot;
I agree.  You and I -- and every citizen -- must re-enlist in
the war against drugs.  If we fail, that bomb will go off in a
crowd of our children.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwold.html.cgi#current">Last Month's Commentaries</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwdaily.html.cgi#current">This Month's Commentaries</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

