<title>Daily Commentary - January 10, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 10, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Here's a &quot;dear Abby&quot; story for you, but it's not about
the famous newspaper columnist who gives advice to the lovelorn.
The Abby I'm talking about is a darling kindergarten girl who
lives in suburban Washington DC.  Her classmates were passing
out Christmas cards and she wanted to share in the holiday joy.

<p>

But Abby's cards contained Bible verses and shared the love of
Jesus with the elementary kids in this local public school.  Believe
it or not, her teacher confiscated Abby's cards.  When her dad
went up to the school to complain, the principal said the materials
were &quot;offensive and inappropriate.&quot;  Apparently, he
hasn't heard the reason for the season.

<p>

Christmas comes but once a year, but this militant, anti-religious
attitude, unfortunately, can be found all year long.  It's not
just uncharitable, it's <I>unconstitutional</I> Supreme Court
rulings have been bad on voluntary school prayer and the religious
rights of students, but <I>no</I> court has gone to this outrageous
extreme.

<p>

We will work to correct these injustices.  We know that as long
as this is America, we don't have to hide our light under a bushel.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

