<title>Daily Commentary - January 13, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 13, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

When the lawyers in favor of assisted suicide stood before our
Supreme Court last week they made all kinds of arguments for what
they called the right to die.  But Justice Antonin Scalia nailed
them with this probing question: &quot;This is <I>lovely</I> philosophy.
Where is it in the Constitution?&quot;

<p>

Now, I've spoken with you about assisted suicide before.  Today,
I want to focus on Justice Scalia's question.  Over the past thirty
years, we have seen a judiciary that is out of control on a host
of issues.  If our judges would only ask themselves Scalia's question,
they would not give in every time some bizarre claim is presented
to them.  Think of the outrageous rulings our courts have handed
down.  Abortion-on-demand. Banning voluntary school prayer.  Approving
flag burning. 

<p>

We need to hold the courts accountable. Abraham Lincoln said
that if we don't,  we will cease to be our own rulers.  Let's
make all our judges answer Justice Scalia's question.  &quot;Where
is it in the Constitution?&quot;

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

