<title>Daily Commentary - January 20, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 20, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

For years Bill Cosby brought family-friendly entertainment into
millions of living rooms.  We identified with the triumphs and trials 
of the Huxtable family.  That's why the sorrow of last week's tragic 
death of Bill Cosby's son Ennis, is shared by Americans everywhere.

<p>

It's also a reminder that we've become a country where the streets
are no longer safe.  Government is failing in its first purpose: to 
protect the safety of its citizens.  We also see from this tragedy that 
the breakdown of reliable standards of right and wrong is deadly.

<p>

You know, this breakdown in values has other consequences.  Like
the callousness of one T.V. network showing footage of Cosby's
son lying in a pool of blood.  Amazingly, the network said &quot;[it]
had no precise rules for airing such footage.&quot;

<p>

Well, folks, that's exactly the problem.  Our society no longer
seems to have precise rules for living.  And until we recover those 
core values, it's no longer safe to stop and change a flat tire.

<p>

For now our thoughts and prayers are with the Cosby family.
May God comfort them in this time of loss.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008. 

