<title>Daily Commentary - January 22, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 22, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

There was a memorable line in Bill Clinton's inaugural address
that bears repeating.  He said: &quot;We cannot, we will not succumb
to the dark impulses that lurk in the far regions of the soul
everywhere.  We shall overcome them.&quot;

<p>

As I listened to the president, I wondered what dark impulses
he had in mind.  Was he talking about the choice movement that
has left over 37 million unborn children dead on this the 24th
anniversary of <I>Roe v. Wade</I>?

<p>

Was he talking about the philosophy that leads government bureaucrats
to take an extraordinary bite out of the paychecks of working
families, only to pay for programs that whittle away at our liberty?
And what about the dark impulses that lead our own government
to give benefits to citizens based on their race instead of judging
the content of their character.

<p>

Sadly, this government has succumbed to all of these bad ideas.
But I hope the President's call to overcome &quot;dark impulses&quot;
will signal a turning point on these issues.  In the weeks and
months ahead let's watch carefully to see whether his actions
match his rhetoric.              

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.  

<p>

