<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - January 31, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 31, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Well, they're at it again.  Politicians who were elected to
Congress claiming to favor a balanced budget amendment are looking
for ways to break their promise.  Why am I not surprised?  Meanwhile
experts here in Washington are predicting that the deficit will
start rising again this year.

<p>

Now this issue affects every family.  The burden of the debt
we are building today will be carried by our children tomorrow.
We have two choices in dealing with the deficit.  The first is
to pass the balanced budget amendment.  The second is to do what
economists call &quot;monetizing&quot; the debt.  Now without
getting too technical, this simply means to print more money.
But every time we do that, we lower the value of dollars already
earned.  That will create huge inflation and wipe out Americans'
savings.

<p>

It's clear that the only way to force Congress to balance the
budget <I>and</I> protect the savings of working families is
to pass the balanced budget amendment.  There's one more thing
we ought to do -- we should tie congressional salaries to progress
on eliminating the debt.  Now there's an idea whose time has come.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.   

<p>

