<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - February 3, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
February 3, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

My family and I enjoy the outdoors.  And like most people we
share a real concern for the environment.  But for the Washington
bureaucrats, what masquerades as concern is just another power
grab.

<p>

In recent years the government has taken control of 100 million
acres of land.  That's roughly equivalent to Ohio, Indiana and
Illinois put together.  Most of the land is privately-owned and
all of it was taken because the government reclassified it as
&quot;wetlands.&quot;  In low-lying Louisiana, the government
has effectively asserted control of over half of all private land.

<p>

But what's really weird is how the government defines &quot;wetlands&quot;.
In fact, land that is dry 350 days a year can still be considered
a &quot;wetland&quot;.  Under this definition even a puddle would
qualify.

<p>

You know, Teddy Roosevelt was one of my favorite presidents.
And he was known for his love of the outdoors.  But that's a
lot different from today's bureaucrats who use concern for things
like the environment and child welfare as cover to take power
from families.

<p>

That's an encroachment we must guard against.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again: 1-800-225-4008.

<p>

