<title>January 30, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 30, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Loralei Gilliam.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>MEDICAL JOURNAL EDITOR IGNORES FACTS IN<br>
PROMOTING LUNACY</h2></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> &quot;The editor of the <I>New England
Journal of Medicine</I> (NEJM) violated one of the first principles
of good medicine by publishing his call for legalizing 'medical'
marijuana,&quot;  FRC senior policy analyst Robert Maginnis said
Thursday, following the release of an NEJM editorial.  &quot;Dr.
Jerome Kassirer ignored readily available government studies and
court decisions.  He is guilty of recommending bad medicine.&quot;

<p>

<B>Maginnis noted that among the many facts overlooked by the
writer was the work of his predecessor</B>. A previous editor
of the NEJM, Dr. Arnold Relman, chaired a 1982 Institute of Medicine
review of the available scientific information on the health effects
of marijuana.  That review was also published in the NEJM and
concludes, &quot;The available evidence is incomplete and much
more work is needed.&quot;

<p>

Dr. Kassirer's editorial cites a 1988 administrative court judge's
decision supporting limited medical use of marijuana, but completely
ignores a 1994 court of appeals decision overruling the earlier
decision.  The appeals court established guidelines requiring
rigorous scientific proof in order to satisfy the requirement
of &quot;currently accepted medical use&quot; for schedule II
drugs. The appeals court also supported the Drug Enforcement Administration's
decision denying re-scheduling of marijuana with the statement,
&quot;The administrator reasonably accorded more weight to the
opinions of the experts than to the laymen and doctors on which
the petitioners relied.&quot;

<p>

Maginnis said, &quot;Dr. Kassirer must be unaware of a <B>1992
National Institutes of Health review which concluded, 'There is
no scientifically sound evidence that smoked marijuana is medically
superior to currently available therapies.'&quot;</B>

<p>

The ongoing debate which Dr. Kassirer now joins is really between
drug legalizers and the American Medical Association, the American
Cancer Society and the American Ophthalmological Society, notes
Maginnis, saying:  &quot;These national organizations have repeatedly
condemned marijuana as medicine in the face of advocates promoting
only anecdotal evidence.

<p>

&quot;Dr. Kassirer says that the determination of safety and efficacy
is irrelevant in persons with advanced illnesses.  But this ignores
many FDA-approved medicines which have superior efficacy and are
available. <B>He must understand that giving crude marijuana
is parallel to providing pond water to a patient when pure water
is available.</B>  No prudent doctor would ever recommend smoking
as medicine given the fact that smoke is highly correlated with
many cancers.

<p>

&quot;He ignores the damage left in the wake of marijuana abuse
and the mixed message so-called 'medical' pot sends to the general
population.  Government studies link pot with many traffic fatalities,
unsafe sex, more alcohol consumption, higher suicide rates, increased
suppression of immune systems especially among AIDS and cancer
patients and numerous lung ailments.

<p>

&quot;Even the often pro-drug nation of The Netherlands recently
declared marijuana unfit medicine.  The December 31, 1996 report
from the Health Council of the Netherlands declares, '...the Committee
has concluded that evidence is insufficient to justify the medical
use of marihuana [sic].'

<p>

&quot;Kassirer's compassion for suffering patients is understandable,
but his ignoring a wealth of conflicting science isn't.  Doctors
need to listen to medical experts and not to the drug lobby.&quot;

<p>

<center><h4>FOR MORE INFORMATION OR INTERVIEWS,<br>
CONTACT THE FRC MEDIA OFFICE AT (202) 393-2100.</h4></center>

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/press/press.html">Other Press Releases</a>]
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/subscribe/subscribe.html.cgi">Subscribe to 
our Press Release E-Mail List</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

<HR SIZE = 3>

<p>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/FRC/images/navstrp2.map">
<img src="/townhall/FRC/images/navstrp2.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
<br>

