<title>January 8, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 8, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2><u>COURT WATCHERS:</u><br>
REMEMBER HOW <i>ROE V. WADE</i> CHANGED AMERICA?<br>
IT COULD HAPPEN AGAIN AFTER TODAY</h2></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> The U.S. Supreme Court is preparing
to hear two cases in January -- one today -- that could change
the face of the life debate. <B>The courts, having decided that
human life did not have intrinsic value at its conception, now
will decide what value it holds at its conclusion.</B>

<p>

THIS IS NOT THE FIRST TIME THAT A NATION HAS STOOD ON THE THRESHOLD.
In a brief to the Supreme Court filed by the Family Research
Council, attorney of record Cathy Cleaver describes the circumstances
in pre-Nazi Germany's medical community that led to euthanasia
and of fateful decisions about &quot;good death&quot; and the
end of human life. Once a nation decides that there is such a
thing as a &quot;life not worth living&quot;, history has shown
that decisions to terminate such lives infect the corridors of
power.

<p>

Neither Germany nor Holland made it legal, per se, to kill through
euthanasia during World War II. The policies were subtly adopted,
and the results are easy to read. What would happen in America
if our courts actually give a legal foundation to wide-spread
&quot;good death&quot;?

<p>

THE FAMILY RESEARCH COUNCIL CAN HELP.  We have experts in the
areas of law and disability who understand the slippery slope
on which the high court is poised by these cases. The implications
of a hasty ruling could change America's health care system and
lead all of us to wonder &quot;who can be trusted&quot; when faced
with a personal medical crisis.

<p>

<center><h4>CALL FRC'S MEDIA OFFICE AT 202-393-2100.</h4></center>

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/press/press.html">Other Press Releases</a>]
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/subscribe/subscribe.html.cgi">Subscribe to 
our Press Release E-Mail List</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

