<title>July 30, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
July 30, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100 or Kristin Hansen.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>ATTENTION: GOP Convention Reporters/Editors

<p>

HOW WILL YOU GET FAST PRO-FAMILY<br>
ANALYSIS FROM AUG. 2-18 ...<br>
CALL: 1-800-236-8538</h2></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> From abortion to the need for pro-family
tax relief -- domestic policy will head the list of hot topics
during the convention news cycle. And to meet the need for conservative
political analysis <b>Gary L. Bauer will be available</b>.

<p>

Called &quot;an influential conservative&quot; by <I>The New York
Times</I> and a &quot;values guru&quot; by <I>Rolling Stone</I>,
Bauer has made a name for himself in politics as a player who
knows how to motivate the grassroots. Bauer was domestic policy
advisor to Ronald Reagan and undersecretary of education for Bill
Bennett. Today, as president of the Family Research Council, Bauer
is well known as point man in Washington for Dr. James Dobson,
head of the largest pro-family organization in America -- Focus
on the Family.

<p>

<b>For arranging interviews during the convention</b>,
the media is invited to call: 1-800-236-8538. In San Diego, the
following number -- with voice mail -- will also be available:
619-233-3980. Additional assistance is available from Washington
D.C. by calling Rebecca Biles at FRC headquarters: 202-393-2100.
After 6 p.m. Eastern, dial extension 223 and your message will
be received.

<p>

Among the pro-family activities scheduled during the convention,
Gary Bauer will be available from 10 a.m. to noon Pacific time
on Tuesday, Aug. 13, for a book signing of his best-selling pro-family
platform, <I>Our Hopes Our Dreams.</I> The event takes place in
the Regency Room of the Horton Grand. Later that day in the same
room, from 4 p.m. to 9 p.m. Pacific, Family Research Council will
host a Capitol Cafe for convention participants.

<p>

