<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>February 7, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>
<LI> Campaign-finance reform is back in fashion. Why? Political favors and outright corruption exist in countries with all sorts of political systems and campaign-finance laws, which suggests that financing is not the central problem. As long as big government gives politicians something to sell, some will be willing even eager to buy. The solution is to bring payments into the open. Publicize all contributions and the names and affiliations of all contributors, whether the funds are intended to get out the vote or to rent the Lincoln bedroom. Abolish public funding of campaigns. Limit the Federal Elections Commission to publicizing where the money comes from. Then, Congress can get on with the real reform or making government smaller. With less to sell, there well be fewer buyers and less money in politics.
<P>
<LI> Indeed, it's shaping up to be a February of defeats for conservatives. Republicans are likely to lose the fight over the Balanced Budget Amendment. Populists will certainly lose on term limits. And  pro-lifers (and spending hawks) may well lose an international abortion-funding vote. Defeat, as Rich Lowry points out in <I>NR</I>, Feb. 24., can be habit forming. If Republicans don't rise from their defensive crouch and set an agenda bolder than their current one, they will be unable to block the Democrats' agenda of targeted tax credits and regulation. If they do, they will find that victory can be habit-forming too.
</blockquote>


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
