<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>February 5, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>


<LI>  John Chafee (R., R.I.),  chairman of the Senate Environment Committee,  has always been a staunch opponent of efforts to deflate scares on global warming, ozone depletion, and so on. But Chafee is starting to upset the greens a bit. Following recent moves by the Environmental Protection Agency to toughen clean-air standards, Chafee has pushed a highly critical congressional letter, accusing the agency of  proposing radical changes in standards without a clear scientific rationale. By shifting the focus from 10-micron dust particles to ones a quarter the size, the agency is admitting that "much of the effort to reduce the health problems . . . may have been focused on the wrong sources." Chafee adds: without "a better understanding of how small particles threaten public health, the proposed standard may similarly result in controls on the wrong sources." The EPA's own Clean Air advisory committee wrote that the agency's new standards could not be shown to be significantly more protective of public health than the old ones. But regulators make their living regulating, so why should they care?

</blockquote>


