<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>February 4, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>






 <LI>

The Clinton Administration has submitted to Congress an "Environmental Crimes and Enforcement Act" which would allow the Justice Department to freeze the assets of a corporation accused of being a pollutereven before trialas it does with drug dealers, on the bizarre grounds that the property was involved in the crime and is therefore culpable. The burden of proof then rests on the accused to prove that his property was not involved. Of course the law is already very imprecise in its definition of a polluter. Under Superfund, the program aimed at cleaning up toxic-waste sites, property owners are held to be "polluters" if they merely own or are connected with property which is deemed to be "polluted." It is no defense to demonstrate that it wasn't you but a former owner who was responsible; under the doctrine of joint and several responsibility anyone who sent any new material to a "hazardous waste" site is liable for cleanup costs. In Pennsylvania a man served two years in jail for violating the Clean Water Act, even though he was able to prove that the pollution of the stream entered his property from an abandoned coal mine further upstream. Of course with carbon dioxide being called "the ultimate pollution" (because of its role in global warming), everyone who breathes can be presumed guilty.
</blockquote>


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
