<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 24, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>





<LI> In much of the media, after the murder of JonBenet Ramsey it became <I>de rigeur</I> to denounce beauty contests for elementary-school girls. What's going on? Frank Rich of the <I>New York Times</I> provides a clue. "Pageantry isn't a subculture," Mr. Rich announced, "it's our culture." By that he didn't mean that 6-year-olds parading around dressed as 20-year-olds is a culture in which Frank Rich feels at ease. Rather, "the children's beauty-pageant biz . . . is a Middle American phenomenon." So the death of JonBenet turns out to be merely another opportunity for bashing the Heartland. It's hard to say what's more distasteful: exploiting little live girls for the pleasure of ogling adults, or exploiting one little dead girl for the pleasure of liberal Heartland-haters.
<P>
 <LI>Paul Tsongas, who died at age 55, waged a gallant fight for his party's presidential nomination in 1992, after a gallant (albeit temporary) victory over cancer. His campaign would have been more memorable if he had not concealed an earlier relapse. Cancer patients deplored this failure, even as they admire his spirit.
</blockquote>


