<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 22, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>






<LI> Remember how anti-Communists were ridiculed for minimizing the indigenous element in the Vietnam War? The National Liberation Front represented a coalition of groups suffering the depredations of U.S.-supported governments in Saigon, we were told, and any support they received from the North was minimal. Well, when the wartime chairman of the NLF, Nguyen Huu Tho, who had become the vice president of Vietnam, died on December 24, the Associated Press's obituary said that Tho "led North Vietnam's political offensive against the U.S.-backed South during the Vietnam War." It also reported, matter-of-factly, that Tho had been chairman of the National Liberation Front, which was "founded in 1960 to help the Communist North overthrow Saigon." Send condolences to Hanoi.  
</blockquote>


