<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 21, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>


 <LI>The committee appointed to investigate "Gulf War Syndrome" has delivered a report, concluding that it does not know what caused the high incidence of illness among Army personnel who fought in Iraq. There is some evidence that U.S. forces may have been exposed to Iraqi nerve gasa possibility that raises drastic questions about deterrence and retaliation. But another question also arises: It was four years before the Pentagon took this matter seriously, and the aroma of a cover-up, negligence, and bureaucratic muddle is strong. Another syndrome may be recognizable: CYA (Cover Your A). Or DMW (Don't Make Waves). Any military organization depends on loyalty, and if it expects loyalty from the men who fight and may die, it must return their loyalty. The Pentagon has defaulted on this duty. 

</blockquote>


