<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 18, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>





 <LI>Drug czar Barry McCaffrey and Attorney General Reno responded to medical-marijuana referenda in California and Arizona by promising action against whoever recommends medical pot or uses it. "It's not just the doctors, it's everyone involved," said Miss Reno. Gen. McCaffrey dismissed abundant testimony to pot's medical efficacy as "Cheech and Chong" medicine. So what is arresting doctors and cancer patients? <I>Naked Gun</I> law enforcement?
<P>
<LI> At its semi-annual meeting of foreign ministers, the North Atlantic Alliance made an important decision in Brussels last month: an allied summit will be held in Madrid next July, at which certain Central European countries will be invited to begin normal negotiations on the North Atlantic Treaty, with the aim of admitting new members by 1999, the Treaty's 50th anniversary. Although not yet named, Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, and possibly Slovenia and Rumania are the leading candidates. For the Senate, it means a vote in late 1998 or early 1999 on extending NATO's defense guarantees eastward.

</blockquote>


