<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 17, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>



<LI>When the founder and leader of the Peruvian Shining Path terrorist movement, Abimael Guzman, was captured a few years ago, William F. Buckley Jr. argued that it would be foolish to keep Guzmana mass murdererin prison, since he would be bait for hostage-taking by terrorists still at large. Terrorists in Peru have killed an estimated fifty thousand people during the last decadethe equivalent of a half-million people in U.S. terms. Keeping Guzman alive is the modern equivalent of keeping Himmler alive while a Nazi movement was still active in the hills. Now a rival group of murderers, the "Tupac Amaro," has seized hostages and is trying to negotiate for the release of its comrades. A terrorist in jail is an invitation to further terrorism. They should be tried promptly and, if convicted, executed.



</blockquote>


