<HEAD>
<TITLE>November Insider -- Of Note -- Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><br>
<h3>Resource Bank</h3><p>
From the October Edition of <i>The Insider</i><br></center>

<center><h2>Of Note</h2></center>


<p>
<b><i>Consumer Product Safety Commision Monitor</i> Launched by Consumer Alert </b>
<p>
Consumer Alert has launched a new publication called <i>CPSC Monitor</i>. It is a series of fax newsletters covering the activities of the Consumer Product Safety Commision (CPSC). The purpose of the series is to educate the public about CPSC actions that negatively impact consumers. With this publication, Consumer Alert hopes to scrutinize CPSC which has greatly expanded its original mission under the Clinton Administration. CPSC has deviated from its original mission with more recalls that have needlessly scared consumers and increased the cost of consumer products. CONTACT: Consumer Alert, 1001 Connecticut Avenue, N.W., Suite 1128, Washington, DC 20036, 202/467-5809, fax 202/467-5814, e-mail calert@aol.com. 
<p>
<b>Institute of American Values Investing</b>
<p>

Socially conservative investors can now fight cultural deficits with their own wallet. The Institute of American Values Investing  is an investment research and public policy company that screens mutual fund portfolios to identify funds which invest in companies that promote or profit from pornography, anti-family entertainment, abortion, and non-marriage lifestyles. They have identified 1,239 of over 7,000 mutual funds as "red light" funds, or funds whose portfolio holdings do not meet the screening criteria. The Institute has created screening analysis software for active fund investors and professional advisors which will be updated quarterly. A newsletter also provides a range of fund information and data to enable individual investors to make informed decisions about their mutual fund investments. CONTACT: Institute for American Values Investing, 5010 148th Ave., N.E., Suite 210B, Redmond, WA 98502. 
<p>
<b>Lecture Series to Examine the Impact of Religious Conviction on Politics</b>
<p>

The Foreign Policy Institute, Paul H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies (SAIS) and the Ethics and Public Policy Center will sponsor a lecture series to examine "The Impact of Religious Conviction on the Politics of the 21st Century." All lectures will be held at SAISin Washington. The purpose of the series is to assess evidence of a worldwide resurgence in religious belief and to reflect on the implications of such a development at the end of the current millennium. Specifically, the project will address the following questions: What are the origins of the revival of religious fervor at the end of the 20th Century? How far and how long will this revival go? What are the chief elements of the critique of the secular order mounted by the various religions and ethical traditions enjoying a resurgence of popularity? To what degree are the religion-based critques rooted in common assumptions and compatible responses to the perceived shortcomings of secularity? What are the implications of this phenomenon particularly as they relate to international politics: prospects of war and peace, economic development, and the definition of human rights and social justice? CONTACT: Alysia Banks, Foreign Policy Institute, 202/663-5772, or William Brailsford, Ethics and Public Policy Center, 202/682-1200.
<p>
<b>Independence Institute Establishes Quarterly Journal on Liberty</b>
<p>

The Oakland, CA-based Independent Institute is now publishing <i>The Independent Review: A Journal of Political Economy</i>. The journal will be edited by historian and economist Robert Higgs, and each issue will feature 160 pages of articles on public policy, social and intellectual history, and political economy broadly construed. It will also feature policy debates, historical retrospectives, commentaries, and book reviews. The recently published issue (Fall '96) includes articles by Bruce Benson and David Rasmussen on civil forfeiture and the drug war, Stephen Shmanske on government failure in health care, Sheldon Richman on opposition to FDR's New Deal, and James Montanye on telecommunications policy. CONTACT: Independent Institute, 134 Ninety-Eighth Avenue, Oakland, CA 94603, 510/632-1366, fax 510/568-6040. 
<p>
<b>National Association of Evangelicals Video on Religious Persecution Around the World</b>
<p>

The National Association of Evangelicals (NAE) has produced a video which documents the problem of religious persecution around the world. NAE calls this situation the human rights issue of the 1990s. A resource kit containing this video and additional information on the persecution of Christians has been put together and mailed out to tens of thousands of pastors across the the country. CONTACT: National Association of Evangelicals, P.O. Box 28, Wheaton, IL 60189, 1-888/LETSPRA.
<p>
<b>National Legal Center for the Public Interest Publishes New Monthly Series</b>
<p>

The October and November issues of <i>BRIEFLY: Perspectives on Legislative, Regulation, and Litigation</i>, address labor law reform and civil justice reform, respectively. Each booklet is based on the panel proceedings of a recent NLCPI conference. Contributors to the labor law publication include lawyers William Kilber and Glen Naer and economist Farell Bloch, each a leading expert. Civil Justice reform panelists were former Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, former Acting Attorney General Suart Gerson, Ford Motor Co. Vice President Jack Martin, and torts authority Victor Schwartz. CONTACT: National Legal Center for the Public Interest, 1000 16th St., N.W., Suite 500, Washington, D.C. 20036, 202/296-1683, fax 202/293-2118.
<p>
<b>Intercollegiate Studies Institute Seeks Manager of Annual Fund</b>
<p>

The Intercollegiate Studies Institute (ISI) is seeking a Manager of the ISI Annual Fund. ISIis a national non-profit educational institution founded in 1953 to further, in successive generations of American college youth, a better understanding of a market economy, limited government, the rule of law, and the matrix of values and institutions that support a free and humane society. For this new position, reporting to the Director of Development, ISI seeks applicants with experience in development, an ability to write well, a college degree, and unbridled enthusiasm for ISI's mission. Major duties include prospecting, writing appeals and acknowledgments, renewing and upgrading donors, working with college alumni, stewardship, producing ISI's newsletter and other publications, and prospect research. Experience in writing proposals and in using Blackbaud Raiser's Edge software a plus. Send resume and letter to Director of Development, Intercollegiate Studies Institute, 3901 Centreville Road, P.O. Box 4431, Wilmington, DE 19807-0431. 
<p>
<b>Reason Foundation Seeks Education Policy Analyst</b>
<p>
Reason Foundation is seeking to fill a full-time position for an education policy analyst. The ideal candidate will have prior knowledge of education policy issues and will have excellent writing and analytic skills. An advanced degree in economics, public administration, public policy, or related fields is desirable. Send resume to: Lynn Scarett, Vice President of Research, Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Boulevard, Suite 400, Los Angeles, CA 90034.
<p>
