<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Taxation &AMP;  Budget</FONT></CENTER>
<P>



<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1091.html">The Case for Repealing the Estate Tax, </a><BR>
</B>by Bill Beach
<P>
<I>Backgrounder</I> No. 1091, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
As long as governments have been collecting taxes, the death of
well-to-do individuals has been a lucrative moment for tax collectors.
The manifestation of such a tax today is the estate tax. Except
the estate tax effects more than just the wealthy, with the hardest
hit being small business owners. Bill Beach, John M. Olin Senior
Fellow in Economics, puts forth the case for repealing the estate
tax, and identifies it as the &quot;worst tax of all.&quot; According
to Beach, the social and economic costs of the estate tax far
exceeds the revenue that it brings to the government. Growing
evidence shows that the estate tax: reduces economic growth, and
hurts the incomes of the people that wealth redistribution was
intended to aid; it increases the cost of capital, this slows
down research and development and the investment in machines that
would increase worker productivity instead-and thus wages; it
keeps the interest rates on home loans and other major purchases
unnecessarily high; and it does not raise very much money-and
may, in fact, cost government and taxpayers more in administrative
and compliance fees than it raises in revenue. Using two leading
econometric models, a Heritage Foundation study found that the
repeal of the estate tax would have a large and beneficial effect
on the economy. According to the analysis, if the tax were repealed
this year, over the next nine years: America's economy would average
as much as $11 billion per year in extra output; an average of
145,000 additional new jobs could be created; personal income
could rise by an average of $8 billion per year above current
projections; and the deficit would actually decline with the revenues
generated by extra growth. Beach points out that that estate tax
has few friends other than tax attorneys. 30 pp. CONTACT: Chris
O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue,
N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/lect569.html">The Flat Tax: Revitalizing the American Dream, </a></B> 
<br>by Walter Williams, Ken Blackwell, John Fund, and Steve Forbes
<P>
<I>Heritage Lecture</I>, No. 569, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
In this <I>Heritage Lecture</I>, Walter Williams, Professor of
Economics at George Mason University, Ken Blackwell, Treasurer
of the State of Ohio, John Fund, Editorial Writer at <I>The Wall
Street Journal</I>,<I> </I>and Steve Forbes, former presidential
candidate and Publisher of <I>Forbes</I> magazine, participate
in a forum on the benefits of a flat tax. Williams starts the
symposium by discussing the morality of taxation. Blackwell talks
about the negative effects of income taxes on the rate of economic
growth, and the perverse incentives of the current federal tax
system to states and local governments. John Fund brings up the
point that the average American family has to work until May 6
in order to earn enough money to pay its state, federal and local
taxes. Finally Steve Forbes stresses that under the current tax
code, The United States cannot reach its potential as a nation.
12 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214
Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058,
fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1090.html">How to Measure the Revenue Impact of Changes in Tax Rates,</a>
</B> 
<br>
by Dan Mitchell
<P>
<I>Backgrounder</I> No. 1090, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
Dan Mitchell, McKenna Senior Fellow in Political Economy, explains
how dynamic scoring should be used to modernize the revenue-estimating
process. Dynamic scoring recognizes that tax policy effects the
economy, as opposed to static analysis, which assumes that tax
changes have no impact on economic growth. Mitchell argues that
dynamic scoring, if used properly, can help bring about sound
tax policy by reducing the politically unpleasant side-effects
of tax cuts. Static analysis does not take into account the fact
that a larger economy created by easing a tax burden brings in
larger revenue to government coffers. Politicians usually support
the idea of cutting taxes. However, they are afraid of being blamed
for the higher deficits that static analysis predicts will happen
with tax cuts. Mitchell lists several points that policy makers
should consider when taking steps to modernize the revenue-estimating
process: learn from history that static scoring overestimates
how much revenue will be generated by a tax increase, while underestimating
the revenue feedback that pro-growth tax changes will generate;
realize that dynamic analysis is not perfect, as opposed to static
analysis which is guaranteed to give the wrong answer; tax cuts
that have a greater effect on behavior, such as a capital gains
tax cut have a greater revenue feedback effect; policy makers
should insist that taxpayers get full disclosure on whatever model
and methodology is used by revenue estimators at the Joint Committee
on Taxation and the Treasury Department; have the goal of tax
policy be the maximization of growth, not tax revenue; and include
the estimated private and governmental compliance costs of taxation.
Mitchell concludes by saying that dynamic forecasting is based
on a proper understanding of how the economy works, and that history
has shown this approach to be more realistic. 17 pp. CONTACT:
Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B>A Fiscal Policy Report Card on America's Governors: 1996,</B>
<br>
by Stephen Moore and Dean Stansel
<P>
<I>Policy Analysis</I>, No. 257, Cato Institute<HR>

<P>
This report from Cato presents an objective, comparative analysis
of the spending and tax policies of 46 state governors. Stephen
Moore, Director of Fiscal Policy Studies, and Dean Stansel, Fiscal
Policy Analyst at the Cato Institute, constructed a 14-variable
index of fiscal performance and applied it to the records of each
governor who took office before 1993. The authors then graded
each of the governors on their fiscal conservatism. George Pataki
of New York, Steve Merrill of New Hampshire, and Fife Symington
of Arizona, received the grade of &quot;A.&quot; Gaston Caperton
of West Virginia, Tom Carper of Delaware, Lawton Chiles of Florida,
and George Voinovich of Ohio received &quot;F's.&quot; A significant
trend that was uncovered by the study was that states have become
more fiscally conservative since 1994, and the new governors as
a class tend to be more fiscally conservative than those elected
before 1993. 84 pp. CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490,
E-mail <a href="mailto:cato@cato.org">cato@cato.org, </a>Internet <a href="http://www.cato.org/">http://www.cato.org/</a>
<P>
<B>Accounting for Growth: Incorporating Dynamic Analysis Into
Revenue Estimation, <BR>
</B>by Gary Robbins and Aldona Robbins
<P>
<I>Policy Report</I> No. 138, Institute for Policy Innovation
<HR>

<P>
Gary Robbins, John M. Olin Senior Research Fellow at the Institute
for Policy Innovation, and Aldona Robbins, Bradley Senior Research
Fellow at the Institute for Policy Innovation, examine the issue
of &quot;dynamic analysis.&quot; Dynamic economic analysis is
the process of estimating economic changes that occur because
of changes in tax policy. It does not assume that all economic
behavior and variables remain the same if tax laws or government
expenditures change. Robbins and Robbins used dynamic analysis
with three hypothetical changes: a per capita tax of $5,200; an
elimination of the capital gains and dividend taxes on individuals;
and a uniform rate for individual and corporate income taxes of
19 percent, all with a commonly accepted baseline of 2.5 percent
annual growth from 1996 to 2010. They found that the head tax
raises GDP 22 percent above baseline by 2010. By removing individual
capital gain/dividend taxes raises GDP 8.5 percent, and the 19
percent uniform rate puts real GDP 7.5 percent above baseline
by 2010. Their use of dynamic analysis suggests tax reform aimed
at growth can increase annual output roughly 10 to 15 percent.
This boost would lead to more jobs, higher incomes, and an expanded
tax base which would bring higher revenues, not losses. 19 pp.
CONTACT: The Institute for Policy Innovation, 250 South Stemmons,
Suite 306, Lewisville, TX 75057, 214/219-0811, fax 214/219-2625,
e-mail <a href="mailto:ipi@i-link.net">ipi@i-link.net, </a>Internet <a href="http://www.ipi.org">http://www.ipi.org.</a>
<P>
<B>From Aberdeen to Wenatchee: Property Taxation in Fifteen Washington
Cities</B>
<P>
<I>Special Report</I>, Washington Research Council<HR>

<P>
This paper is the second in a series of reports on the property
tax system in the state of Washington. Each community varies in
its reliance on the property tax. The Washington Research Council
examines the property tax burden in fifteen diverse cities and
communities. The diversity of experience is lost in a statewide
aggregation. In the profiles of the fifteen cities, the Washington
Research Council presents valuation changes, looks at the property
tax collected by each of the major tax-levying jurisdictions,
identifies the degree to which each major local government relies
on property taxes as a share of its budget, and examines briefly
the voter-approved levies. 22 pp. CONTACT: Washington Research
Council, 1301 5th Avenue, Suite 2810, Seattle, WA 98101, 206/467-7088,
800/294-7088, fax 206/467-6957.
<P>
<B>The Hidden Heir: How Estate Taxes Are Swallowing up Family
Businesses And Farms-And How We Can Stop It</B>
<P>
Public Policy Institute of New York<HR>

<P>
The Public Policy Institute of New York examines the detrimental
effects of New York's state-level estate and gift taxes. With
federal estate taxes, and the additional burden of New York state's
top rates reaching 76 percent, owners of family businesses and
farms are often times forced to flee New York when they retire,
taking valuable assets with them. Most states do not add to federal
estate taxes, but simply take some of the tax that otherwise would
go to the federal government. New York collects the most revenue
of the states that do levy estate or inheritance taxes and has
the highest top rates on inheritance to children. Contrary to
the nationwide trend of states repealing their death taxes, New
York has been expanding its estate tax. This paper argues that
New York must reduce its rates, reduce the burden of the state
gift tax; conform estate tax credits to the federal level; and
make policy changes that can ease the transfer of family businesses
from one generation to the next. Finally, this paper argues that
New York could go further than a reduction in disadvantages, and
create an actual incentive for family businesses to locate in
New York state. By establishing a New York Sate Family Business
Fund, the fund could loan family businesses and farms money to
pay federal estate taxes. It would be capitalized with a small
share of exiting estate revenue flow-so that revenues from the
rich would pay for keeping family businesses and their jobs in
New York. 27 pp. CONTACT: The Public Policy Institute of New York
State, 152 Washington Avenue, Albany, New York 12210, 518/465-5263.
<P>
<B>Public-Private Promises #1: Three Rivers Stadium,</B><br>
by Grant Gulibon
<P>
<I>Report</I>, No. 96-14 Allegheny Institute<HR>

<P>
In light of the proposal to build a new government subsidized
baseball stadium in Pittsburgh, Grant Gulibon, Research Associate
at the Allegheny Institute, examines the rosy promises made in
a similar proposal approximately thirty-five years ago for Three
Rivers Stadium. Gulibon's report examines the claims used to justify
the construction of Three Rivers Stadium and contrasts them with
the stadium's actual performance since its opening. He found:
the original estimated cost of the stadium was $13.8 million,
while its final cost is estimated to be between $52 and $62 million;
the 83.5 acre site where the stadium was built was estimated to
cost $10 million in 1958, re-estimated to cost $21.72 in 1962,
but ultimately cost $45 million; Three Rivers Stadium was to be
a &quot;self-financing&quot; project which would not require city
or county operating support, but, has run up a $43 million deficit,
and has received operating subsidies for the Allegheny County
Regional Asset District; very little of the predicted private
development plans for the area surrounding the stadium exists
due to a lack of market demand; Through 1991 the city had over
$100 million on the stadium, still owes $40 million on the bonds
floated for the original construction, and had provided $27.1
million in subsidies for stadium operating deficits over the same
time period; deficits continued even after the stadium authority
hired a private management group to manage Three Rivers in 1982;
and St. Louis' Busch Stadium, four years older than Three Rivers
and nearly identical in size and design, privately financed and
has been privately owned and operated since it opened, was completed
under budget, has turned a profit each year since it opened, and
has been cited by baseball officials as one of the model facilities
in operation today. 19 pp. CONTACT: Allegheny Institute, 7 Parkway
Center, Suite 612, Pittsburgh, PA 15220, 412/937-4526, fax 412/928-1501.

<P>
<B>Restoring Opportunity to Arkansas: Changing a &quot;Tax and
Spend&quot; State to a &quot;Save and Invest&quot; State,</B>
<br>
by Stephen Moore and Dean Stansel
<P>
Arkansas Policy Foundation
<P>
Stephen Moore, Director of Fiscal Policy Studies at the Cato Institute,
and Dean Stansel, Fiscal Policy Analyst at Cato, discuss how changing
the tax policy in the state of Arkansas, would restore opportunity
to the state. In Arkansas, tax and spending has exploded over
the past fifteen years. Moore and Stansel list several examples
of Arkansas' heavy taxation: state spending is 50% higher than
it was in 1980-and spending has risen 12% faster than state income
in the same period; if the state budget had only grown at the
rate of personal income growth, Arkansas could both balance its
budget and give every family in the state a $1,000 tax rebate;
Arkansas' high tax burden is 15% above the national average, and
is weakening the state's competitiveness with other states; spending
priorities have been radically rewritten since 1980, from traditional
state responsibilities such as education, highways, and hospitals
to less productive and more redistributive goals such as welfare,
public health, and debt service; and that the state budget has
been growing at an annual rate more than twice that of inflation.
To solve these tax problems, Moore and Stansel offer the following
spending restraints and tax cuts: a 25% cut in personal income
tax rates, eventually to become a 5% flat tax to deliver economic
growth; indexation, which prevents state government from benefiting
through inflation; eliminate the state capital gains tax on new
investment, to have a giant impact on investment and job growth;
enact a one-year budget freeze to allow the rest of the state
to catch up; and finally, implement a constitutional budget cap
that prevents growth of spending from rising faster than the growth
rate of the state population plus inflation. Moore and Stansel
conclude that such measures have led to stunning economic success
in states as  different as Massachusetts, Michigan, and New Jersey.
 16 pp. CONTACT: Arkansas Policy Foundation, 8201 Cantrell Road,
Suite 325, Little Rock Arkansas, 72227, 501/277-4815, fax 501/227-8970,
e-mail <a href="mailto:Aggiemw2@aol.com">Aggiemw2@aol.com.</a>
<P>
<B>Taxation and Economic Performance, <BR>
</B>by W. Kurt Hauser
<P>
<I>Essay in Public Policy</I>, Hoover Institution<HR>

<P>
Kurt Hauser, President of a San Francisco investment management
firm, argues that increased tax rates do not raise the desired
additional revenues. In his essay he shows that the economy as
a whole tends to perform worse following a tax increase. Reduction
in tax rates, however, tends to make the economy perform more
favorably. Hauser notes that economists have debated for the past
two centuries over whether or not higher rates of taxation leads
to increased levels of government revenues. More recently, he
points out, the revenue generation forecast for the tax increase
of 1990 and 1993 fell short of the mark. According to Hauser,
higher tax rates tend to reduce the tax base because of the disincentives
that they cause to work, produce, save, or invest. There are also
incentives to hide, shelter, and underreport income when tax rates
are raised. Policy makers still continue to believe that increases
in marginal tax rates will raise revenues without the adverse
effects on economic growth, job creation, or standard of living.
30 pp. CONTACT: Hoover Institution Press, Stanford University
Press, Stanford, CA  94305-6010, 415/723-3373, fax 415/723-1687,
Internet  
<a href="http://hoover.stanford.edu./">http://hoover.stanford.edu./</a>

