<b>Judging an Interest Group by the Politicians it Keeps: An Analysis of NEA-PAC Contributions to House Races,</b> by John Berthoud<p>
<i>Issue Brief</i> No. 120, Alexis de Tocqueville Institution<p>
John  Berthoud, Vice President of the Alexis de Tocqueville Institution, relates that a review of contributions by the political action committee of the National Education Association reveals that the Congress that NEA is seeking to elect would radically change the direction of American government. Most significantly, NEA's ideal Congress would vastly expand federal spending and taxation. The average House candidate supported by the NEA during the last election cycle had an agenda to increase federal spending by $302 billion per year. On the other hand, the candidates that the NEA opposed had a net agenda to cut federal spending by $22.6 billion per year. Berthoud also states that, despite NEA's pledge of support for America's children, if NEA could have the Congress it wanted, it would mean either hundreds of billions of dollars in new taxes on American families or hundreds of billions of dollars in deficits for future generations. 7pp.  CONTACT: The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution, 1611 North Kent Street, Suite 901, Arlington, VA  22209, 703/351-4969, fax 703/351-0090.
<p>
<a href="/heritage/library/categories/education/cb26.html">Why Vouchers Are Needed for Poor Children,</a> by Denis P. Doyle<p>
<i>Committee Brief</i> No. 26, The Heritage Foundation<p>
Denis Doyle, Heritage Visiting Fellow in Education, argues that Congress has a historic opportunity to convert Title I, Education for the Disadvantaged, into a voucher program. He proposes that poor families, rather than bureaucrats, decide where their children will go to school. Doyle cites the widely recognized problems with Title I, including the adverse effect of the Supreme Court's Aguilar decision which actively discourages poor children from attending non-government schools by penalizing them if they do. Doyle concludes that in order to reform Title I, the program should be reconnecting to its true beneficiaries-students and not schools. As it is, Title I commits more than $1,000 to each eligible child and if that money were available as a Title I voucher it would permit children to select schools that best serve their needs. Such an approach, writes Doyle, would mitigate the effects of the school bureaucracy and begin to instill values which foster character development. 5pp.  CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<b>Bilingual Education in Massachusetts, The Emperor Has No Clothes,</b> by Christine H. Rossell and Keith Baker<p>
Pioneer Institute for Public Policy Research<p>
Christine Rossell, Professor of Political Science at Boston University, and Keith Baker, a private social science research consultant, thoroughly examine the bilingual education program in Massachusetts public schools for limited English-proficient (LEP) students. They look at the controversial aspects of bilingual education nationwide,and they survey the history of bilingual education in Massachusetts.  Rossell and Baker provide eight recommendations for improving edicuational programs for LEP students: 1) free school districts from the legal obligation to provide native language instruction; 2) increase the LEP population size needed to trigger a self-contained classroom; 3) require parental consent for enrollment in a self-contained classroom; 4) require English language fluency for teachers in an educationl program for LEP children; 5) change the criteria for entering and exiting a self-contained classroom; 6) eliminate specific class-sized ceilings; 7) better research that would allow social scientists to analyze the success of the programs; and 8) the ideal program is that which involves "structured immersions." 242 pp. CONTACT: Pioneer Institute For Public Policy Research, 85 Devonshire Street, 8th floor, Boston, MA 2109, 617/723-2277, fax 617/723-1880.
<p>
<b>The Heartland Report on School Finance Reform for Illinois,</b> by Joseph L. Bast, Herbert J. Walberg, and Robert J. Genetski<p>
<i>Policy Studies</i> No. 72 and 73, Heartland Institute<p>
Joseph L. Bast, President of The Heartland Institute, Herbert J. Walberg of the University of Illinois at Chicago, and Robert J. Genetski of Chicago Capital, Inc., formulate a reply to the Governor's Commission on Education Funding and offer alternative principles for school finance reform. The report cites evidence which demonstrates why public schools are failing in Illinois, such as excessive bureaucracy and regulation. Moreover, the writers maintain that spending more money will not alleviate the situation. They argue that student achievement is not related to spending because increased spending rarely addresses the reasons schools are failing. The second part of the report offers a means to improve public schools through a market-based approach. The plan incorporates parental choice, private school choice, competition, and curriculum based exams to improve the quality, and the means to gauge the quality, of public schools. CONTACT: The Heartland Institute, 800 East Northwest Highway, Suite 1080, Palatine, IL  60067, 708/202-3060, fax 708/202-9799, e-mail <a href="mailto:think@heartland.org">think@heartland.org,</a> Internet <a href="http://www.heartland.org">http://www.heartland.org.</a>
<p>
<b>With Liberty and Justice for All: Redefining the Educational Choice Debate,</b> by Jennifer A. Marshall and Jennifer E. Marshall,<p>
<i>Family Policy,</i> Family Research Council<p>
Jennifer A Marshall, Educational Policy Analyst for the Family Research Council, and Jennifer E. Marshall, Welfare Policy Analyst for the Family Research Council, survey the philosophical and historical background of public education. They assert that, given the failure to establish a full educational choice program anywhere in the U.S. after a quarter century, choice proponents must challenge themselves to develop a new scheme. The proposal should place a premium on liberty and on the private benefits of education while reformulating the public-purpose rhetoric employed by the education establishment. Marshall and Marshall also believe the new proposal should avoid the weaknesses associated with vouchers, including the menace of government regulation, consistent challenges to constitutionality, dim prospects for political passage, the danger of expanding an entitlement mentality and a narrow coalition of beneficiaries to support passage. The authors invest faith in a refundable tax credit scheme to overleap the hurdles presented by means tested voucher programs. 7pp.  CONTACT: Family Research Council, 700 13th Street, N.W., Suite 500, Washington, DC  20005, 202/393-2100, fax 202/393-2134, Internet <a href="http://www.frc.org">http://www.frc.org.</a>
<p>
<b><i>Right to Read Report</i></b><p> 
National Right to Read Foundation<ul>
<p><li><b>Governor George W. Bush Speaks Out,</b>  Vol. 3, No. 2. This issue features excerpts from Governor George W. Bush's speech to the Texas Education Agency outlining his concerns about literacy. 2pp.
<p><li><b>The Bicoastal Uprising Against Whole Language,</b> by Dr. Patrick Groff,  Vol. 3, No. 1. This issue focuses on the nationwide effort to block the promotion of the "Whole Language" approach to reading development. In addition, the issue features a piece relating the facts a parent should know about Attention Deficit Disorder (ADD). 2pp. 
<p><li><b>Pro-Phonics Lawmakers Want Answers,</b> Vol. 2, No. 7. The seven pro-phonics members of Congress relate their concern about the attacks by the Federal Trade Commission on "Hooked on Phonics." Also, efforts and reasons to abolish the Department of Education are presented in different articles. 1pp. 
<p><li><b>The Federal Trade Commission Attacks "Hooked on Phonics,"</b> Vol. 2, No. 6. The newsletter centers on the Federal Trade Commission's attack on "Hooked on Phonics." The Commission maintains that an individual can not be taught to read without a tutor or teacher, despite years of research that has found the opposite to be true. In addition, reasons to abolish the Department of Education are presented by William Bennett and Lamar Alexander. 2pp.
</ul><p>CONTACT: The National Right to Read Foundation, James B. Jacobson, 3220 N Street, N.W., Suite 174, Washington D.C. 20007. <P>
