<head>
<title>July-August Insider -- Resource Bank -- Heritage</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><br>
<h3>Resource Bank</h3><p>
From the July-August Edition of <i>The Insider</i></center><br>
<hr>
<h2>Magazines & Journals</h2><p>


<b><i>City Journal </i></b><br>
Summer 96, Manhattan Institute<p>
This issue of <i>City Journal</i> features an article by Contributing Editor Sol Stern entitled "The Invisible Miracle of Catholic Schools." Stern illustrates how inner-city Catholic schools in New York have educated some the neediest and uneducable kids from the city's most troubled neighborhoods, for a third of what taxpayers spend per pupil for the city's public schools. Despite the proven success of Catholic schools, Stern notes that liberals have ignored them in their search for solutions to the problems of New York's ailing public schools. Other articles in this issue include: "Special Ed: Kids Go In, But They Don't Come Out," by Kay Hymowitz; "Why L.A. is Bouncing Back," by Joel Kotkin; and "Reinventing the Port Authority," by Dick Netzer.  CONTACT: The Manhattan Institute, 52 Vanderbilt Avenue, New York, NY 10017, 212/599-7000.
<p>
<b><i>Governing</i></b><br>
July 1996<p>
Tom Arrandale, examines what one might expect with the transition from monopolies to competition in the power industry. Arrandale points out that although competition, by nature, brings lower prices, it may raise the price of power for less savvy purchasers. Other articles in this issue include: "Fish Tales," by Charles Mahtesian, which examines the aquarium building binge in several cities in recent years; "Ruckus Over Rating," by Penelope Lemov, which examines controversies in the bond rating system that could bring more government regulation; and "A Dollar's Worth of Government," by Jonathan Walters, which tries to determine exactly what one unit of government service costs. CONTACT: Governing, 2300 N St. N.W., Suite 760, Washington, D.C. 20037, 202/862-8802, fax 202/862-0032. 
<p>
<b><i>Headway</i></b><br>
July 1996<p>
This issue of <i>Headway</i> features several articles on the issue of what is "authentically black." Joseph Brown, an Editorial Writer with the <i>Tampa Tribune,</i> tells about when his "blackness" was question when he came out on a different side of a policy issue than the civil rights establishment. Meanwhile, Sharon Brooks Hodge shares a story of when her "authenticity" as a black was questioned because she is "articulate." Ron Freeman, President of The Freedom Foundation in Summit, Missouri, argues that authentic blackness should mean being free and responsible to one's self and family, rather than shifting blame and avoiding responsibility. Finally, Jacqueline Gordon, founder and Director of the Christian Women's Forum, laments that too many African-Americans see black "authenticity" and "genuiness" linked to being politically liberal. These viewpoints show how broad generalizations about blacks are enforced within the black community itself and how this serves to work against the original ideals of the civil rights movement. 38 pp.  CONTACT: <i>Headway,</i> 13555 Bammel N. Houston, Suite 227, Houston, TX 77066, 713/444-4265, fax 713/583-9534, e-mail <a href="mailto:wrichardson@ghgcorp.com">wrichardson@ghgcorp.com,</a> Internet <a href=" http://www.townhall.com/nmp">http://www.townhall.com/nmp.</a><p>

<b><i>The American Spectator</i></b><br>
August 1996<p>
In this issue, <I>American Spectator's</i> Senior Correspondent, John Corry, examines the Clinton Administration's attempt to feminize the military, appearently without regard for high rate of pregnancies on co-ed aircraft carriers. He suggests that "the people who did not wnat thier boys to go to Vietnam, Central America, or the Persian Guulf now want the girls to go everywhere else." the politization of the military threatens to undermine its primary reason for existing, "to fight and win wars." In another article entitiled "Bill's Mary Poppins," Rebecca Borders, a Washington Reporter, profiles long time Clinton advisor Betsy Wright. Also, Paul Johnson, author of <i>Modern Times</i>, and more recently, <I>The Quest for God</i>, reviews Alonzo Hamby's biography of Harry Truman entitiled <i>A Man of the People</i>. 86 pp. CONTACT:<i>The American Spectator</i>, 2020 North 14th Street, Suite 750, Arlington, VA, 22201, 703/243-3733, or 800/524-3469, e-mail <a href="mailto: amspec@ix.netcom.com">amspec@ix.netcom.com.</a><p>

<b><i>Regulation</i></b><br>
1996 No. 2, Cato Institute<p>
This issue of <i>Regulation</i> examines the topic of state regulations. Articles include the following: "State Regulatory Measures," by Edward Hudgins, Director of Regulatory Studies at The Cato Institute; "Time to End the Economic War Between the States," by Lawrence Reed, President of The Mackinac Center for Public Policy; "Promises Unfulfilled: The Unfunded Mandates Reform Act of 1995," by Angela Antonelli, Deputy Director of Economic Studies at The Heritage Foundation; "Rhetoric vs. Reality: New Jersey Regulatory Reform," by Dana C. Joel, Deputy Director of Regulatory Policy at Citizens for a Sound Economy; "Virginia's Deregulatory Challenge: A Promising Start," by Susan Eckerly, Director of Virginia Citizens for a Sound Economy; and "Modernizing of Zoning: A Means to Reform," by George Liebmann, a Baltimore lawyer. CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490, e-mail <a href="mailto: cato@cato.org">cato@cato.org</a>, Internet <a href="http://www.cato.org">http://www.cato.org.</a><p>

<b><i>Carolina Journal</b></i><br>
April-May 1996, John Locke Foundation<p>
The April-May <i>Carolina Journal</i> centers on an articled entitled "Lemon and (Sub)Lime: Why We Must Re-engineer State Government." In this article, John Hood, President of the John Locke Foundation, compares state government to the U.S. auto industry to demonstrate the need for political leaders to take risks and be innovative. He finds that over the last 20 years the per-capita cost of state government in north Carolina and the price of a new car grew by about 70 percent in real terms. During the same period of time, however, the quality of these two products moved in separate directions. Concerning education and social services, increased state spending has not shown significant gains in education achievement and a key indicator in social well-being_the number of illegitimate births_has gotten worse. Meanwhile, during the same period of time, the struggling American automobile industry has dramatically improved and has reclaimed a competitive position in the world market. According to Hood, the comparison gives three lessons from the auto industry to state government: 1) competition is essential; 2) managerial flexibility is key; and 3) focus on results is crucial.  CONTACT: The John Locke Foundation, P.O. Box 17822, Raleigh, NC  27619, 919/847-2690.
<p>
<b><i>Reason</i></b><br>
August/September 1996, Reason Foundation<p>
The cover story in this special double issue of Reason is entitled "Can Washington Change?" Jonathan Rauch, author of <i>Demosclerosis: The Silent Killer of American Government</i>, says "no." Rep. Chris Cox, Ed Crane, Steven Hayward, Susanne Lohmann, William Mellor III, Grover Norquist, John Pitney, and Randy Simmons contribute responses as well. CONTACT: Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Boulevard, Suite 400, Los Angeles, CA  90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395.
<p>
<b><i>Impact</i></b><br>
Spring 96, Foundation for Florida's Future<p>
This issue features articles on crime. Chuck Colson, former aid to President Nixon and Founder of Prison Fellowship Ministries, argues that returning to the basics of teaching children right and wrong will help lower future crime. Princeton's John Dilulio assesses the juvenile crime situation in Florida and shows that a future wave of "superpredators" is on its way. He calls for punishing juveniles as adults and to build on community-based, faith-based private programs. CONTACT: Foundation for Florida's Future, 3399 Ponce de Leon Boulevard, P.O. Box 144155, Coral Gables, FL 33134, 305/442-0414, fax 305/442-2215, e-mail <a href="mailto: Sally@fff.org">Sally@fff.org,</a> Internet <a href="http://www.fff.org">http://www.fff.org.</a><p><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map">
<IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP width=540 width=67 BORDER=0></A></CENTER>
</body></html>


