<h3>Resource Bank</h3><p>
From the July-August Edition of <i>The Insider</i></center><br>
<hr>
<h2> Of Note</h2><p>


<b>The Post-Modernity Project Launched</b><p>
The Post-Modernity Project at the University of Virginia was recently launched with "a vision and commitment to offer critical insight and resources to all concerned with responding creatively and strategically to the challenges posed by this time of unprecedented social transformation."  The Project's publication, entitled <i>Echoes,</i> will be published bi-annually.  CONTACT: James Davison Hunter, University of Virginia, B5 Garret Hall, Charlottesville, VA  22903, 804/924-7705.    
<P>
<b>Independence Institute Creates Parent Information Center</b>
<p>
The newly created Parent Information Center (PIC) is designed to provide the parents of Colorado with the consumer information they need to make the right school choices for their children. The Center has accumulated information on almost every public school in Colorado.  Based on this information, the PIC has made available report cards for every school to help parents in the school selection process.  CONTACT: Independence Institute, 14142 Denver West Parkway, Suite 185, Golden CO  80401, 303/279-6536.
<p>
<b>Comprehensive Charter School Directory</b>
<p>
The Center for Education Reform announced the release of the Center's National Charter School directory, the first comprehensive listing of America's charter schools.  CONTACT: The Center for Education Reform, 1001 Connecticut Av. NW., Washington, DC 20036, 202/822-9000, e-mail <a href="mailto: cerd@aol.com">cerd@aol.com.</a>
<p>
<b>The Importance of History</b>
<p>The Center for the Study of History was founded to promote the study of history, encouraging its application in the workplace, and demonstrating how basic scholarship connects with nonacademic careers. To this end, the NCSH publishes educational material, advises teachers and students, and otherwise supports projects with compatible concerns.  CONTACT: National Center for the Study of History, Rural Route #I, Box 679, Cornish, ME  04020, 207/637-2873.
<p>
<b>New Monthly <i>Culture Watch</i></b><p>
Capital Research Center in June begian publishing <i>Culture Watch,</i> a monthly newsletter which intends to spotlight trends, ideas and personalities that "enrich the arts and cultural life."  CONTACT: Capital Research Center, 727 15th Street NW, Suite 800, Washington D.C., 20005-2168, 202/393-2600.
<p>
<b>FREE's 5-Day Seminars for Federal Judges</b>
<p>
The Foundation for Research on Economics and the Environment (FREE), has scheduled three federal judge seminars to be held in Montana in 1996. The main objectives of FREE's program are to "increase the judiciary's knowledge and understanding of the importance of prosperity and economic efficiency to environmental quality, and to increase the importance of bringing sound analysis to risk management." The seminars will be held during the following dates:  June 15-20, August 21-25, September 17-22.  CONTACT:  FREE, 945 Technology Boulevard., Suite 101F, Bozeman, MT  59715, 406/585-1776, fax 406/585-3000. 
<p>
<b>William Bratton Joins Council on 
Crime in America</b><p>
Former U.S. Attorney General Griffin B. Bell and former Drug Czar William J. Bennett, Co-chairs of the Council on Crime in America, announced that William J. Bratton is joining the Council. Mr. Bratton stepped down as New York City Police Commissioner on April 15th after having presided over an unprecedented decline in violent crime in the city.  The Council on Crime in  America was established last year to study the scope of violent crime and to identify effective, community-based anti-crime strategies.  CONTACT:  The Council on Crime in America, 1150 17th Street, NW, Suite 510, Washington DC  20036, 202/822-8333, fax 202/822-8325.
<p>
<b><i>Ultimate Issues</i> Gives Way to <i>The Prager Perspective.</i></b><p>
After writing Ultimate Issues for 11 years, Dennis Prager will embark on a new venture, a twice-each-month publication to be called The Prager Perspective.  Prager writes essays on "life's great issues," as he described them, with special attention to Judaism.  CONTACT:  Dennis Prager, 3710 S. Robertson Blvd., Culver City, CA  90232, 310/558-3958, fax 310/558-4241.  <p><p><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map">
<IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP width=540 width=67 BORDER=0></A></CENTER>
</body></html>


