<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/libary/categories/budgettax/bg1072.html"> A Progress Report on Closing Unneeded And Obsolete Independent Federal Agencies,</a>  
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Ronald Utt</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.1072, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Ronald Utt, Visiting Fellow at the Heritage Foundation, examines what has been accomplished by 
Congress this session in closing unneeded and obsolete government agencies. He finds that Congress has 
done a respectable jobespecially in relation to past Congressesbut that there is much more to be done. 
They did better than most observers expected, closing over 270 agencies, divisions, offices, and programs 
of various areas of the federal government. Utt also looks at what actions Congress took in 41 specific 
agencies recommended for termination by the Heritage Foundation. Excluding the five independent 
agencies that are not subject to the annual appropriations process, Utt found that Congresss record of the 
remaining 36 was: 13 agencies terminated and $3.6 billion saved over the next five years; funding for 12 
agencies substantially reduced by 10 percent or more) and $2.2 billion saved over five years; and no 
change or only limited change (funding cut by 10 percent or less) at 11 agencies and up to $40 million 
saved over the next five years. Utt also shows that of the 11 agencies not significantly reduced in funding 
terminated, all but onethe Franklin Delano Roosevelt Memorial Commission, whose funding was 
tripledsaw their funding either modestly reduced or frozen at 1995 levels. Despite Congresss proven 
effort to reduce government waste, Utt points out, President Clinton opposed many of these efforts by 
vetoing five of the appropriations bills put forth by Congress. He concludes by outlining termination and 
consolidation objectives for the FY 1997 budget. 20 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage 
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-
0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>.<p>

