<CENTER><font size=5>EDUCATION</font></CENTER>

<P>
<B>Why Colorado Should Drop out of Goals 2000, <BR>
</B>by Sheldon Richman
<P>
<I>Issue Paper</I>
No. 2-96, The Independence Institute

<P>
Sheldon Richman, Policy Analyst at the Cato Institute,
examines each of Goals 2000's &quot;goals.&quot; He finds that
each goal will lead to more intrusion by the federal government,
and ultimately to federal control of curriculum, teaching practices,
and even facilities. Although Goals 2000 supposedly has &quot;no
power,&quot; and purports to build upon existing local efforts
to improve education, Richman argues that achievement of its goals
will require a drastic expansion of federal control. Richman also
shows that non-compliance with &quot;voluntary&quot; Goals 2000
directives could lead to litigation by the federal government
against states and local school districts. Richman focuses his
attention on Colorado's experience with Goals 2000 and the ominous
trends that followed its entry into the program. He found that
local educators and elected boards are losing their freedom to
set agendas, teach in ways they find effective, and monitor their
own progress. Richman concludes that although Goals 2000 is supposed
to bring excellence to schools, in reality it enacts increased
federal intrusion into families, communities, local school boards,
and state legislatures. 17 pp. CONTACT: Independence Institute,
14142 Denver West Pkwy., No. 101, Golden, CO  80401, 303/279-6536,
fax 303/279-4176. 
<P>
<B>Goals 2000 and California Education: Devolution
or Retreat? </B>by
Lance Izumi &amp; Natalie Williams
<P>
<I>Briefings </I>No. 1995-47, The Claremont Institute
<P>
In this study, Lance Izumi, Senior Fellow in California
Studies and Co-Director of the Center for Innovation in Education
at the Pacific Research Institute, and Natalie Williams, Director
of Education Affairs at the Claremont Institute, examine the fine
print in Goals 2000 and look at how this program will affect California's
public education system. Izumi and Williams find that Goals 2000
threatens to dominate and control state and local school leaders
by concentrating decision making power with a few un-elected officials
in Washington. They conclude that Goals 2000 represents &quot;devolution
in retreat&quot; and a step backward, toward the centralization
of education authority and responsibility. 28 pp.  CONTACT: The
Claremont Institute, 250 West First Street, Suite 330, Claremont,
CA 91711, 909/621-6825, fax 909/626-8724, e-mail <a href="mailto: 2026935@mci
l.com">2026935@mcimail.com</a>,
Internet <a href="/claremont">http://www.townhall.com/claremont</a>.<BR>

<P>
<B>Arizona School Choice Trust: Survey of Participating
Families, </B>by Tara
Ellman
<P>
<I>Arizona Issue Analysis</I>
No. 138, Goldwater Institute

<P>
Tara Ellman, Education Consultant,
disputes some of the most widespread claims of those that oppose
school choice in this survey of participants in the Arizona School
Choice Trust (ASCT). ASCT is an organization that provides half-tuition
grants to low income parents who wish to send their children to
private schools. The survey found: low-income parents are willing
to subsidize the cost of their child's education; academics, not
religion, is the most frequently cited reason parents give for
choosing private schools; family structure  does not necessarily
dictate level of involvement in a child's education (about half
of the children participating in this program come from single
parent families); school choice programs do not result in &quot;white
flight&quot; (sixty-five percent of the participants are from
minority households); and school choice programs are not necessarily
expensive to administer (disbursement of funds for the ASCT is
done solely by volunteers, so that 100 percent of the money raised
can go to scholarships). 15 pp. CONTACT: Goldwater Institute,
Bank One Center-Concourse, 201 N. Central Ave., Phoenix, AZ  85004,
602/256-7018, fax 602/256-7045.<BR>

<P>
<B>Restoring School Board Options on <BR>
Contracting Out, </B>by
Myron Lieberman
<P>
<I>Briefings </I>No.
1995-48, The Claremont Institute


<P>
Myron Lieberman, Chairman of the Education Policy
Institute, examines the issue of &quot;contracting out&quot; or
&quot;competitive contracting&quot; concerning school boards'
decisions on how to provide certain school services. For example,
a school board might have to make a decision whether to hire school
bus drivers and buy school buses, or to make a contract with a
transportation company to transport its students to and from school.
Lieberman shows that school boards and school board organizations
are unprepared to deal with such decisions because there has been
a massive union effort to restrict or eliminate school board freedom
to contract services. He illustrates this point by outliningthe
efforts that the National Education Association, the American
Federation of Teachers and the AFL-CIO have put forth to prevent
school boards from using the option to contract out school services,
in an effort to protect their own self interests. Lieberman concludes
that school boards &quot;should make every effort to retain or
to expand their authority to utilize contracting out.&quot; 17
pp.  CONTACT: The Claremont Institute, 250 West First Street,
Suite 330, Claremont, CA 91711, 909/621-6825, fax 909/626-8724,
E-mail <a href="mailto: 2026935@mci
l.com">2026935@mcimail.com</a>, Internet <a href="/claremont">http://www.townhall.com/claremont</a>.
<BR>

<P>
<B>Who Got It Right? What Proponents and Opponents
of the Creation of the Department of Education Promised &amp;
Predicted, <BR>
</B>by John Berthoud
<P>
The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution


<P>
John Berthoud, Vice President of The Alexis de Tocqueville
Institution, examines the debate over the creation of the Department
of Education and reveals that original supporters over-stated
the potential benefits and failed to acknowledge many potential
problems. Included is a compilation of promises and predictions
by supporters and opponents of the Department. For opponents,
it was found that many of their predictions have come true. According
to Berthoud these areas that proponents overstated the Departments'
benefits include:  overhead and bureaucracy; efficiency; local
control; cost; and values. 19 pp.  CONTACT: The Alexis de Tocqueville
Institution, 1611 North Kent Street, Suite 901, Arlington, VA
 22209, 703/351-4969, fax 703/351-0090.
<P>
<B>Are Michigan History Textbooks Reliable? <BR>
</B>by Burton Folsom
<P>
<I>Mackinac Center Report</I>,
Mackinac Center
<P>
Burton Folsom, Senior Fellow in Economic Education
with the Mackinac Center, reviews four grade school textbooks
on Michigan state history. The first two texts are written for
junior high or high school students; the other two are for fourth
graders. Folsom argues that a major problem in Michigan education
today is that the textbooks used to teach Michigan history are
often times filled with distorted interpretations and omit important
historical events, figures or trends. He rates the textbooks from
one to four stars based on each text's clarity, organization,
information, balance and lack of bias. 28 pp. CONTACT: Mackinac
Center for Public Policy, 119 Ashman St., P.O. Box 568, Midland,
MI  48640, 517/631-0900, fax 517/631-0964.<BR>
