<a name="environment"</a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><br>
<CENTER><font size=5>ENVIRONMENT, ENERGY &AMP; SCIENCE</font></CENTER>
<P>
<B>How to Dismantle the Interior Department, <BR>
</B>by Robert Nelson
<P>
Competitive Enterprise Institute
<P>
Robert Nelson, Senior Fellow in Environmental Studies
at the Competitive Enterprise Institute, proposes a radical reorganization
of the Interior Department and its functions, based on the following
four principles: 1) activities that can reasonably be carried
out in the private sector should be done privately; 2) activities
that mostly involve state and local concerns should be administered
by state and local governments; 3) the federal government should
limit its role to activities and concerns that involve major federal
interests and responsibilities; 4) administrative organization
at the federal level should place similar functions at the same
agency. According to Nelson, the result of applying these principles
would be the abolition of six of the ten current agencies located
within the Department of the Interior, and a sharp reduction in
the size of three others. Nelson estimates that the proposed reorganization
would save roughly $3.8 billion annually. 19 pp. CONTACT: Competitive
Enterprise Institute, 1001 Connecticut Ave., N.W., Suite 1250,
Washington, DC  20036, 202/331-1010, fax 202/488-0806.<BR>

<P>
<B>How and Why to Transfer BLM Lands to the States,
</B>by Robert Nelson
<P>
Competitive Enterprise Institute
<P>
Robert Nelson, Senior Fellow in Environmental Studies at the Competitive
Enterprise Institute, calls for the transfer of Bureau of Land
Management (BLM) lands to the states. He argues that such a transfer
would improve rangeland management and restore local autonomy
in Western states. Nelson comments on current legislation on the
subject and  concludes his study by offering a series of principles
that could provide the basis for a formal transfer arrangement.
50 pp.  CONTACT: Competitive Enterprise Institute, 1001 Connecticut
Ave., N.W., Suite 1250, Washington, DC  20036, 202/331-1010, fax
202/488-0806.<BR>

<P>
<B>The Smog-Reduction Road: Remote Sensing vs. The
Clean Air Act, </B>by
Daniel Klein <BR>
and Pia Maria Koskenoja
<P>
<I>Policy Analysis </I>No.
249, The Cato Institute
<P>
Daniel Klein, Assistant Professor of Economics at
the University of California at Irvine, and Pia Maria Koskenoja,
a doctoral student of transportation economics at UC Irvine, argue
that existing technology can make unpopular and burdensome vehicle
emission tests obsolete with no reduction in environmental protection.
Remote-sensing-mobile, roadside, emission sensing devices-would
prove more effective and less costly than current inspection-based
emission programs. Klein and Koskenoja point out that 20 percent
of cars on the road generate 88 percent of automobile air pollution,
and contend that current state inspection and maintenance programs
are inefficient in reducing emissions. Remote-sensing technology,
on the other hand can target the small percentage of polluting
motorists for citation by mail. The study, which is based on several
implementation plans of Los Angeles, notes that the costs of a
remote sensing system would be far less than current programs.
Klein and Koskenoja conclude by calling for amending the Clean
Air Act to allow localities to implement remote-sensing programs.
43 pp. CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts Ave., N.W.,
Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490, E-mail
<a href="mailto: gregory@cato.org">gregory@cato.org</a>, Internet <a href="http://www.cato.org">http://www.cato.org</a>.<BR>

<P>
<B>The Misuse of Science in Environmental Management,
</B>by Hugh Ellsaesser
<P>
<I>Heartland Policy Study</I>
No. 70, The Heartland Institute
<P>
Hugh Ellsaesser, a retired scientist from the Lawrence
Livermore Laboratory, examines the problem of the misuse of science
when managing environmental problems. Ellsaesser illustrates such
misuse in the debates concerning air pollution, stratospheric
ozone, and global warming. Ellsaesser concludes that government
bureaucrats and small cliques of politically active scientists
are helping to implement public policies that are not based on
sound science, that impose huge financial costs on hundreds of
millions of people, and that may endanger the lives of billions
of people around the world. 31 pp. CONTACT: The Heartland Institute,
800 East Northwest Highway, Suite 1080, Palatine, IL  60067, 708/202-3060,
fax 708/202-9799, e-mail <a href="mailto: think@heartland.org">think@heartland.org</a>,  <BR>
Internet <a href="http://www.heartland.org">http://www.heartland.org</a>.<BR>

<P>
<B>Environmental Risk</B>
<P>
<I>Economic Affairs</I>
Vol. 16, No. 1, Institute of Economic Affairs
<P>
This issue includes a symposium on the issue of &quot;risk&quot;
in relation to how policy-makers interpret hazards in risk-assessment
in public policy issues. Participants in the symposium include:
Roger Bate, Director, IEA Environment Unit; John Adams, Reader
in Geography at University College, London; Fred Smith, President
of the Competitive Enterprise Institute; James Fanu, Medical Columnist
of <I>The Sunday Telegraph</I>; Niall Fraser, Director of Risk
&amp; Opportunity Intelligence Limited; and David Lascelles, Resources
Editor of the <I>Financial Times</I>. According to Bate, the papers
in this symposium cover enough areas of the subject of environmental
risk-from social anthropology to toxicology and climate science
to credit ratings-to give an assessment of the environment today.
Overall, the papers draw the conclusion that the public perception
of environmental hazards are distorted from the reality of the
hazards. 54 pp. CONTACT: Institute of Economic Affairs, 2 Lord
North St., London, England  SW1P 3LB, 071-799-3745.<BR>
