<h2>Legal Action</h2>

<B>Defenders Represents Property Owners</B>
<br>
<P>
Defenders of Property Rights has argued the case
of <I>Gayle Butcher v. Planning and Zoning Board of Appeals of
Highland Beach</I> before the Maryland Court of Special Appeals.
This appeal raises the issue of whether local government can,
through zoning reclassification, deprive an owner of the use of
a lot to build a single-family home in a fully developed subdivision.
The Butchers and another family bought adjoining lots, one with
a house and the other vacant but developable. The Butchers later
sold the developed parcel and assumed the undeveloped lot with
the intention of building a new home there. The city, however,
said that a zoning ordinance enacted after the lots were originally
purchased precluded them from building on the lot. A decision
is expected to be handed down from the court this Spring.<B> 
<BR>
</B>
<P>
CONTACT: Defenders of Property Rights, 6235 33rd
Street, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20015, 202/686-4197, fax 202/686-0240.
<BR>

<P>
<B>LANDMARK LEGAL FOUNDATION</B>
<P>
<B>Landmark Challenges State-Financed Insurance Scheme</B>
<P>
The Foundation is challenging the constitutionality
of an unprecedented government-created and subsidized insurance
company that is unfairly competing with private insurance companies
in Missouri. This &quot;corporation&quot; has the significant
advantages of a state agency, but does not have the political
accountability safeguards of a state agency. The case is expected
to be tried this summer with a likely appeal to the Missouri Supreme
Court following.<BR>

<P>
CONTACT: Landmark Legal Foundation,
2345 Grand Avenue, Suite 2310, Kansas City, Missouri 64108, 816/474-6600,
fax 816/474-6609.<BR>

<P>
<B>INSTITUTE FOR JUSTICE</B>
<P>
<B>Institute Lauds Decision Allowing Landowners to Exclude Trespassers</B>
<P>
The case filed by the Institute on behalf of Jon
and Josephine Bronczyk defending their private property rights
as owners of &quot;public water wetlands&quot; overcame a big
hurdle on February 5, 1996. Interpreting a Minnesota statute that
appeared to give the public access to privately owned wetlands,
Anoka County District Judge Edward W. Bearse ruled that &quot;it
appears that the plaintiffs would be justified in posting their
land 'no trespassing' and/or 'no hunting,' in seeking the removal
and prosecution of any trespassers, and in actively enforcing
all of their rights as owners of private property.&quot; The judge
granted the defendant Department of Natural Resources' (DNR) motion
for summary judgement to dismiss the case, but on the grounds
that the DNR made concessions during the lawsuit that brought
the agency into agreement with the Bronczyks, thus eliminating
the controversy.<BR>

<P>
CONTACT: The Institute for
Justice, 1001 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W. Suite 200 South, Washington,
D.C. 20004, 202/457-4240, fax 202/457-8574.<BR>

<P>
<B>NATIONAL RIGHT TO WORK LEGAL DEFENSE FOUNDATION</B>
<P>
<B>National Right to Work Defends Against Compulsory Union Dues
for Politics</B>
<P>
After more than ten years of delay, the National
Labor Relations Board announced a key ruling in . <I>California
Saw and Knife </I>which undermines employees' legal protections
against the use of compulsory union dues for politics. The ruling
completes NLRB deliberation on over 100 charges filed by employees
against the International Association of Machinists (IAM). <BR>

<P>
The employees, some of whom initiated legal action
in October, 1985, objected to the union's use of their compulsory
union dues for politics and other activity unrelated to collective
bargaining. National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation attorneys
challenged IAM's forced unionism policy. Despite clear precedents
such as the Supreme Court's 1988 decision in <I>Communications
Workers v. Beck</I>, which allows employees to cut off the use
of their forced dues for activity unrelated to collective bargaining,
contract administration, and grievance adjustment, the NLRB developed
new legal standards governing employees in forced-unionism situations.
<BR>

<P>
Specifically, the NLRB ruled that IAM union officials'
annual &quot;notice&quot; in their internal propaganda magazine
was sufficient to satisfy an employee's right to have notice before
compulsory dues were extracted from a paycheck. In addition, the
Board held that the union can force workers to pay for activities
outside the workers' collective bargaining unit, in direct contradiction
to Supreme Court rulings in <I>Lehnert v. Ferris Faculty Association</I>
and <I>Ellis v. Brotherhood of Railway, Airline and Steamship
Clerks</I>. <BR>

<P>
CONTACT: National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation,
8001 Braddock Road, Suite 600, Springfield, VA 22160, 703/321-8510,
800/336-3600.<BR>

<P>
<B>SOUTHEASTERN LEGAL FOUNDATION</B>
<P>
<B>Of Spanish Land Grants and Federal Government Takings</B>
<P>
SLF has appeared this month as <I>amicus curiae</I>
before the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit in a case
that combines unique historical perspective with potential landmark
legal significance. In <I>Beggerly v. United States</I>, the appellate
court will consider the question of the validity of a Spanish
land grant predating the Louisiana Purchase of 1803 and the U.S
Department of Interior's failure to disclose the existence of
the grant during its 20-year attempt to take the land in question
<BR>

<P>
Pursuant to 1971 congressional authorization to acquire
the land as a federal park, and the Department of Interior's subsequent
below-market price offer, the federal government filed suit in
1979, claiming that Mr. Beggerly's title to the land was void
because of the alleged absence of a valid patent. Over the next
ten years, Mr. Beggerly attempted to locate evidence of title
ownership, discovering at the National Archives an 1871 Spanish
land grant conveying the property to a private landowner filed
with the U.S. Land Commissioners in 1816. His appeal, based on
the recently discovered evidence of title, challenges the lower
court ruling that no such evidence existed, and that the federal
government therefore owed Mr. Beggerly nothing for his land. An
appellate decision is expected in early Fall.<BR>

<P>
<B>Minority Set-Aside Challenge Moves Forward</B>
<P>
SLF filed suit against the Atlanta School District,
challenging the district's policy of artificially lowering minority
bids on open-bid contracts by as much as 15 percent. In <I>Prior
Tire Company v. City of Atlanta School District</I>, SLF is challenging
the set-aside program under the authority of <I>Richmond v. Croson</I>,
a landmark U.S. Supreme Court decision which held that public
contracts, whether local or state, cannot be awarded in whole
or in part based solely on race. SLF was actively involved in
the prosecution of <I>Croson</I>, and seeks to extend that ruling
to the Atlanta program.<BR>

<P>
CONTACT: Southeastern Legal Foundation, 2900 Chamblee-Tucker
Road, Building 4, Atlanta, GA 30341, 404/458-8313, fax 404/458-3960.
<BR>

<P>
<B>WASHINGTON LEGAL FOUNDATION</B>
<P>
<B>&quot;Official English&quot; Supported in Supreme Court</B>
<P>
WLF, joined by 21 Members of Congress, filed a brief asking the
Supreme Court to review the appeals court ruling in <I>Yniguez
v. Arizonans for Official English</I> that struck down Arizona's
&quot;official English&quot; law, which requires that the state
and local governments of Arizona must act in English. The law
contains exceptions allowing a government to act in a language
other than English to protect public health or safety, to protect
the rights of crime victims or criminal defendants, or to comply
with federal law, such as federal requirements that mandate bilingual
education. The appeals court held that the law was not justified
by the goal of encouraging unity and political stability, encouraging
a common language, and protecting public confidence in government
operations. WLF's brief before the Supreme Court argued that the
issue is of national significance and that states have the authority
to determine the language of government business.<BR>

<P>
<B>HUD Opposed in Attempt to Regulate Homeowner's Insurance</B>
<P>
In <I>Nationwide Mutual Insurance Co. v. Cisneros</I>,
WLF filed a brief before the U.S. Supreme Court arguing that the
U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development lacks the authority
to regulate homeowner's insurance under the fair Housing Act.
WLF noted that HUD's interpretation would undermine long-standing
and legitimate insurance practices, and force consumers to bear
higher costs, by exposing insurance companies to liability for
employing standards that are not intentionally discriminatory
but that have a disparate impact on minorities. For example, many
insurers refuse to insure a property for more than its market
value; a policy that disproportionately limits insurance availability
in low-income areas where the replacement value of a home is often
more than its market value. According to WLF's brief, Congress
never intended for federal regulators to intrude on this traditional
area of state regulation.<BR>

<P>
<B>Anti-Gang Loitering Law Defended</B>
<P>
On behalf of itself, Representatives Henry Hyde and
Philip Crane, and four Chicago neighborhood associations, WLF
urged the Supreme Court of Illinois to review a decision striking
down a Chicago ordinance that prohibits members of a criminal
street gang from loitering on city streets after being directed
to &quot;move on.&quot; The ordinance was adopted in response
to strong community pressure to reduce the presence of gang members
of city streets. WLF's brief rejected the defendants' arguments
that the ordinance is unconstitutional because it is overly vague,
violates the right to freedom of assembly, and criminalizes one's
status as a gang member.<BR>

<P>
CONTACT: Washington Legal Foundation, 2009 Massachusetts
Ave., N.W., Washington, D.C. 20036, 202/588-0302.
<P>
