<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/fyi82.html">Balanced Budget Talking Points #8</a>: How a Capital
Gains Tax Cut Would Boost State Revenues, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
William Beach</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>F.Y.I. </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
82, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Heritage Visiting Fellow in Tax Analysis William
Beach found that a cut in the capital gains tax would create a
one-year state income tax windfall of $9.5 billion and estimates
that states that tax capital gains would likely see their income
tax revenues increased by an average of 11.6 percent. 3 pp. CONTACT:
Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail Insider@heritage.org.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/fyi83.html">Balanced Budget Talking Points #9</a>: Why Tax Relief
Is Necessary in a Balanced Budget, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by William Beach
&amp; John Barry</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>F.Y.I. </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
83, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>William Beach, Heritage Foundation Visiting Fellow
in Tax Analysis, and John Barry, Heritage Policy Analyst, used
one of the principal economic models of the U.S. economy to project
the effects, fiscal and economic, of eliminating the tax relief
elements of the congressional Balanced Budget Act. They found
the following: the congressional plan vetoed by the President
would add $112 billion more to Gross Domestic Product (GDP) over
the next seven years than the same plan would without tax cuts;
furthermore, the cuts in taxes on capital (including the capital
gains tax cut) accounts for $66 billion of this additional GDP
and leads to a stronger economy in the long run. This report also
details the benefits of reducing taxes on family income. 5 pp.
CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail Insider@heritage.org.</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Would a Flat Tax Flatten the Housing Market? 
<BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Rebecca Schaefer</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Issues Analysis </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
17, Citizens for a Sound <BR>
Economy Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Citizens for a Sound Economy Analyst Rebbeca Schaefer
argues that a flat tax would not negatively affect the housing
market. While real estate lobbyists claim that the housing market
would be hurt by a  flat tax because it eliminates the mortgage
interest deduction, Schaefer illustrates that families and individuals
do not buy homes because of the tax incentive of a mortgage interest
deduction. Instead, people buy homes for many other reasons: to
relocate, to have more living space, to downsize living space,
to find a better community, etc. Schaefer presents economic evidence
suggesting that a flat tax would bring a drop in mortgage interest
rates by at least 2 percentage points, more than compensating
for the loss of the interest deduction. 8 pp.  CONTACT: Citizens
for a Sound Economy, 1250 H St., NW, Suite 700, Washington, DC
 20005-3908, 202/783-3870, fax 202/783-4687.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>The Fairness of a Flat Tax, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Alan Reynolds</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Hudson Briefing Paper</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 185, Hudson Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Alan Reynolds, Director of Economic Research at the
Hudson Institute, argues that economic progress is affected by
incentives, among the strongest being marginal tax rates on capital
and the way policy treats consumption and savings. Reynolds writes
that high, progressive taxes suppress capital formation, increase
inequality, and reduce real tax receipts. He calls for an increase
in the incentives to save and invest, with time and money, in
education and training. A low flat tax, according to Reynolds,
would increase the economy's stock of economic and human capital,
which would enlarge national wealth, decrease economic inequality,
and increase tax revenues. 12 pp.  CONTACT: Hudson Institute,
Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919, Indianapolis, IN  46226,
317/545-1000, 317/545-9639, Internet http://www.hudson.org/hudson
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Eating Out Our Substance (II): How Taxation Affects
Investment, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Gary Robbins and <BR>
Aldona Robbins</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Policy Report </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
134, Institute for Policy Innovation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Senior Research Associates for TaxAction Analysis,
Gary Robbins and Aldona Robbins, write that more business investment
in new equipment and technology is necessary for increased job
creation and wage growth, but currently high taxes on capital
directly discourage this needed investment. In addition, Robbins
and Robbins argue that the denial by government revenue estimators
that any relationship exists between the tax on capital and capital
formation must be corrected during upcoming tax reform, in order
to avoid unintended consequences and missed opportunities for
the economy and the budget as happened in 1986. 31 pp.  CONTACT:
The Institute for Policy Innovation, 25 South Stemmons, Suite
306, Lewisville, TX  75057, 214/219-0811.<BR>
</FONT>
