<P>
<B><font size=3>The Budget 1996: Why Deep Cuts are Needed and
Where to Make Them, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Yitzhak Klein</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Policy View </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
16, The Shalem Center National <BR>
Policy Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Bar-Ilan University Department of Political Science
Professor Yitzhak Klein explains why Israel's budget needs to
be cut and lists recommendations as to where 8 billion Shekels
worth can be made. Examples of cuts include unnecessary areas
of administration, cost-overrun reserves, social services, and
subsidies to bankrupt firms. He warns against the type of growth
that Israel had between 1993 and 1995, which according to Klein,
was due to excess consumption-driven largely by the government's
ever-increasing budgets. The results of this increase in government
spending has been a large trade deficit and foreign debt, high
inflation, and declining productivity, savings and competitiveness.
29 pp.  CONTACT: The Shalem Center National Policy Institute,
118 Montgomery Ave., Suite B3-1, Balla Cynwyd, PA 19004, 610/667-6709.
