<P>
<B><font size=3>The Wisconsin Welfare Revolution, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Lawrence Mead</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Wisconsin Interest</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
Vol. 4, No. 2, Wisconsin Policy Research Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>In this article, New York University Professor Lawrence
Mead examines why Wisconsin's welfare caseload declined 26% since
reforms and new programs were enacted in 1987. According to state
figures, welfare in the average Wisconsin county fell 42%, while
some small counties recorded decreases of as much as 66%. Mead
found that the decline in welfare recipients was due less to Wisconsin's
now thriving economy and more to the priority that reforms placed
on self reliance. Furthermore, Mead writes that Governor Thompson's
conservative, but not necessarily anti-government, policy was
successful in changing the attitudes of most welfare personnel.
Indeed, most welfare officials, according to Mead, appreciated
that the Governor challenged them with the responsibility of getting
recipients to work, rather than just handing out aid. 8 pp.  CONTACT:
Wisconsin Policy Research Institute, 3107 N. Shepard Ave., Milwaukee,
WI  53211, 414/963-0600, fax 414/963-4230.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Compassion Gone Mad, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Heather Mac Donald</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>City Journal</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,
The Manhattan Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Heather Mac Donald argues that New York's failed
war against social disintegration stems from the failure of the
City and State's welfare programs to give moral guidance. Mac
Donald concludes that the city ought to restore the distinction
between the deserving and the undeserving poor, observing that
experience has shown that those who behave the most irresponsibly
recieve the most city revenues. 11 pp. CONTACT: The Manhattan
Institute for Public Policy Research, 52 Vanderbilt Avenue, New
York, NY 10017, 212/599-7000, fax 202/599-3494.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Public Health Lobby's Attempt To Control High-Risk Behavior
a Threat to Personal Freedom,</B> <BR>
by Jacob Sullum
<P>
<I><font size=3>Reason</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,<I>
</I>January 1996</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Jacob Sullum, Senior Editor
of <I>Reason</I>, argues that the public health establishment's
attempt to prevent illness and injury by controlling certain high-risk
behaviors, such as smoking and alcohol is misleading and a threat
to personal freedom. He argues that when public health officials
assume that certain behaviors are unhealthy, they &quot;treat
adults like incompetent children.&quot; Even when people know
about hazards, to smoke, drink and behave in certain ways not
recommended by the health establishment, they continue not becuse
they misunderstand, but because &quot;for the sake of pleasure,
utility, or convenience, they are prepared to accept the risks.&quot;
CONTACT: Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Blvd., Suite 400,
Los Angeles, CA  90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>The Homeschooling Movement: Giving Homework a
Good Name, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Susan
Olasky</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Philanthropy Culture &amp; Society</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,
Capital Research Center</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Children's author and homeschooling mother Susan
Olasky illustrates the daily activities of several homeschool
families. She writes that most parents homeschool for religious
reasons or because they believe that public or private schools
do not have strong enough academic standards. Regardless of the
reason. However, Olasky maintains that homeschooling has proven
very successful at educating children</FONT><I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">-</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">to
the consternation of the education establishment. At last year's
NEA convention, members voted in an anti-homeschool resolution
advocating its regulation. Overall, concludes Olasky, homeschoolers
feel the benefits of their method of education outweighs their
sacrifices. 8 pp.  CONTACT: Capital Research Center, 727 15th
St., NW, 8th Floor, Washington, DC  20005, 202/393-2600, fax 202/393-2626.
