<P>
<B><font size=3>Rights Worth Preserving, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Becky Norton Dunlop</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Land Rights Letter </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Vol.
5, No. 11 &amp; 12</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>In the lead story of this issue, Becky Norton Dunlop,
Secretary of Natural Resources in Virginia, calls for upholding
the Fifth Amendment against environmentalists who want to water
down its stance on protecting property. Despite the fact that
the Constitution states that no person shall be &quot;deprived
of life, liberty, or property without due process of the law,&quot;
Dunlop describes people who will argue that &quot;a higher good
is served when society places certain restrictions on property
rights rather than slavishly adhering to the Fifth Amendment's
exhortation.&quot; Dunlop suggests  that those who support the
Bill of Rights have the responsibility to fight the charges by
environmentalists that property rights advocates are just rich
developers who want free reign to pollute as they please. 13 pp.
 CONTACT: Land Rights Letter, P.O. Box 1111, Gloversville, NY
 12078, 518/725-8835.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Brownfields: Superfund's Economic Toxic Shock,
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Michael Harrold</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Issues Analysis</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 18, Citizens for a Sound <BR>
Economy Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Unintended consequences of environmental laws, especially
the federal Superfund law, has led to the proliferation of so-called
brownfield sites in American cities. Brownfield sites are &quot;abandoned
or vacant commercial and industrial properties suspected of containing
at least low levels of environmental contamination.&quot; Such
sites have lost potential developers to fears that a consequence
of owning and cleaning up a site will be state or federal liability
and regulation. Therefore, &quot;lenders will not lend, developers
will not develop, and buyers will not buy.&quot; Citizens for
a Sound Economy Policy Analyst Michael Harrold calls for Superfund's
liability and cleanup standards to be fundamentally reformed.
Until then, concludes Harrold, neither the states and EPA, nor
developers and lenders, will have the assurances or authority
under law to bring solutions to the brownfield problem. 18 pp.
 CONTACT: Citizens for a Sound Economy, 1250 H St., NW, Suite
700, Washington, DC  20005-3908, 202/783-3870, fax 202/783-4687.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>The Misuse of Science in Environmental Management,
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Dr. Hugh Ellsaesser</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Policy Study </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
70, The Heartland Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Dr. Hugh Ellsaesser, retired scientist from the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory, reviews examples of the inappropriate
use of science in debates over environmental issues. The essay
begins by showing that misuse of science is a widely recognized
problem, especially in politics and popular culture. Ellsaesser
then delves into three issues where the misuse of science has
been tolerated: the debate over air pollution; the debate over
stratospheric ozone; and the debate over global warming. 31 pp.
 CONTACT: The Heartland Institute, 800 East Northwest Highway,
Suite 1080, Palatine, IL  60067, 708/202-3060, fax <BR>
708/202-9799, e-mail think@heartland.org, Internet <a href="http://www.heartland.org">http://www.heartland.org</a>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Smog in America: The High Cost of Hysteria, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Kenneth Chilton
&amp; Christopher Boerner</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Policy Study </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
128, Center for the <BR>
Study of American Business</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Despite vast improvements in air quality since the
1990 Clean Air Act Amendments, this paper reports that environmentalists
and the American Lung Association are quietly pressuring EPA to
establish a new standard for measuring safe levels of ozone<I>-</I>one
that will be more costly to meet, but may produce little, or no,
meaningful health benefits. Authors Kenneth Chilton, Director
of the Center, and Christopher Boerner, CSAB Fellow, note that
people are already frustrated under the current policy. Programs
such as centralized vehicle inspection and maintenance will increase
the hassle to drivers but may not be an improvement over existing
decentralized programs. Ozone requirements increase costs to individuals
via higher prices and taxes, and impact small businesses more
than large firms. Chilton and Boerner recommend that Congress
revisit the Clean Air Act and allow cost and benefits to be considered
in setting the ozone standard. They conclude: &quot;Unless chronic
effects of prolonged exposures to elevated ozone can be demonstrated
(and after two-and-a-half decades of research, they have not been),
the United States is already spending more taxpayer and consumer
dollars on reducing ozone than the public considers worthwhile.&quot;
28 pp.  CONTACT: Center for the Study of American Business, Washington
University, Campus Box 1208, St. Louis, MO 63130-4899, 314/935-5630,
fax 314/935-5688.<BR>
<BR>
