<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>ECONOMIC &AMP; POLITICAL THEORY</FONT></CENTER>


<P>
<B><font size=3>The Supreme Court's Role in American Federalism,
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Richard Cordray</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3>Federalism Summit: Restoring Balance in the <BR>
Federal System</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Former Ohio State Solicitor Richard Cordray describes
the Supreme Court's role in the uniquely American system of federalism.
He writes that the Supreme Court has been a reluctant and relatively
ineffective umpire on the issue of the allocation of political
power concerning federalism, commenting that it is itself an arm
of the federal government</FONT><I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">-</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">so
state officials should not rely too heavily on the Court as the
ultimate guardian of state interests. Those interested in reviving
the role of the states and federalism should, according to Cordray,
reconsider whether institutional changes could be made to strengthen
the authority of the states and establish a more balanced partnership
with the federal government. 23 pp. CONTACT: Council of State
Governments, 444 North Capital Street, Suite 401, Washington,
D.C. 20001, 202/624-5408, fax 202/624-5460.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Federalism: An Overview, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Philip Burgess</FONT>
<P>
Federalism Summit: Restoring Balance in the <BR>
Federal System
<P>
<font size=3>Philip Burgess, President of the Center for the New
West, addresses three issues in this paper concerning federalism:
1) the recent American experience with federalism; 2) the forces
at work reviving federalism; and 3) a potential framework for
considering ideas about where the federalsim debate should go
from here. He concludes by writing that restoring federalism requires
at least major legislation, if not a constitutional amendment
to restore power and relationships destroyed by the seventeenth
amendment, which removed state legislatures' authority to elect
U.S. Senators. Burgess warns that whatever approach is taken,
the pursuit of principle-centered remedies and not quick fixes
is key. 10 pp.  CONTACT: Council of State Governments, 444 North
Capital Street, Suite 401, Washington, D.C. 20001, 202/624-5408,
fax 202/624-5460.</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Restoring Constitutional Government, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Roger Pilon</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Cato's Letters</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 9, The Cato Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Roger Pilon, Director of the Center for Constitutioanl
Studies at the Cato Institute, argues that it is time to start
returning power to the states and the people, to relimit federal
power in fundamental law, and to restore constitutional government.
Pilon recommends that Congress take the following actions to achieve
this end: 1) declare that the Constitution remains a document
of limited federal powers; 2) declare that most of what the federal
government does today is done without constitutional authority;
3) identify the precise constitutional authority for doing so
before enacting any new legislation; 4) restore the Commerce Clause
to its original purpose; 5) restore the General Welfare Clause
to its original purpose; 6) restore the Necessary and Proper clause
to its orignal purpose; and 7)  restore those provisions of the
Bill of Rights and the Civil War Amendments that have fallen into
disregard-privileges and immunities, property rights, and economic
liberties. 24 pp.  CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts
Ave., NW, Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490,
e-mail gregory@cato.org, Internet http<BR>
://www.cato.org.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Suedosclerosis: The Problems of Swedish Economy,
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Ingemar St&aring;hl
&amp; Kurt Wickman</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3>Timbro Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">In the 1993 book <I>Suedosclerosis</I>,
The Swedish economists Ingemar St&aring;hl and Kurt Wickman discuss
the factors that have contributed to the crisis in the Swedish
economy and introduce the terms &quot;relative price shock&quot;
and &quot;relative interest shock.&quot; In 1994's <I>Suedosclerosis
II</I>, St&aring;hl and Wickman argue that the Swedish crisis
is deeper and the adjustments slower than in comparable countries.
They conclude that political responsibility must be transfered
from the public sector to the private sector, and fundamental
changes in the welfare systems are necessary in order to abolish
the politics of high taxation. This particular publication contains
excerpts from both books. 66 pp.  CONTACT: City University Press,
Box 5234, S-102 45 Stockholm, Sweden, e-mail info@cityuniv.se.
<BR>
</FONT>
</BODY>

<a name="legal"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a>
<center><h2>Legal Action</h2></center>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>ATLANTIC LEGAL FOUNDATION</FONT></B>


<P>
<B>Senators Challenge Executive Order</B>
<P>
<font size=3>ALF represents United States Senators Paul Coverdell
of Georgia and Slade Gorton of Washington in a challenge to President
Clinton's Executive Order that bars federal agencies from doing
business with companies which hire permanent striker replacements.
Through the brief, the two  Senators take the position that the
Executive Order violates the principle of separation of powers
in that the question of striker replacements involves labor policy
which is the prerogative of Congress to establish. In fact, Congress
years ago established such a policy in the National Labor Relations
Act in an effort to counter-balance the power of the labor unions
to call strikes. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>ALF Urges that Exposure to EMF Does Not Cause Discernible Harm</B>
<P>
<font size=3>Representing 14 distinguished scientists, including
5 Nobel laureates, ALF submitted a brief in the Supreme Court
of California involving a question of whether exposure to electromagnetic
fields can cause cancer. The scientists conclude that the evidence
does not justify the fears advanced by the plaintiffs in an action
against San Diego Gas &amp; Electric Co. that low intensity electromagnetic
fields from power lines can cause cancer.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: Atlantic Legal Foundation,
205 East 42nd Street, Ninth Floor, New York, NY 10017, (212)573-1960,
Fax (212)573-1959. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>CENTER FOR INDIVIDUAL RIGHTS </FONT></B>


<P>
<B>CIR Sues University for Speech Violation</B>
<P>
<font size=3>The Center and co-counsels, representing the Florida
ACLU and the Southeastern Legal Foundation, are representing Gerald
Gee, a professor at Florida A&amp;M University who was suspended
without pay for an in-class remark allegedly constituting discrimination
and harassment. In illustrating a point, the professor used the
term &quot;nigger&quot; although he did not direct the term at
any individual. At issue in this case is whether Gee's remark
to his students is protected under the scope of academic freedom.
After CIR brought a lawsuit in early 1995, asserting claims under
both the Equal Protection and Free Speech clauses of the U.S.
Constitution, and sought a preliminary injunction revoking the
suspension, Florida A&amp;M agreed to rescind the remaining portions
of Gee's suspension. Professor Gee's claims for damages and further
injunctive relief are pending before the district court.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Update on CIR's Sex Discrimination Appeal</B>
<P>
<font size=3>The Center is representing five male professors at
Virginia Commonwealth University who claimed sex discrimination
when the school gave a raise to only female professors in 1992.
This summer, the Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the
lower court's decision that granted summary judgment to VCU. The
Court of Appeals held that the case should go to trial since the
pay raise was justified by a &quot;salary equity test&quot; that
failed to take into account such critical factors as teaching
performance, publications, and service to the community. However,
the full Fourth Circuit granted VCU's petition to rehear the case
<I>en banc</I>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: Center for Individual
Rights, 1300 Nineteenth St., NW, Suite 260, Washington, DC  20036,
202/833-8400, fax 202/833-8410.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>DEFENDERS OF PROPERTY RIGHTS </FONT></B>


<P>
<B>Defenders Seeks to Protect Landowners</B>
<P>
<font size=3>For over a hundred years, the boundaries for some
parcels of land owned in Kamiah, Idaho have been established and
respected. Yet, it turns out that the title descriptions in their
deeds do not reflect these boundaries. At the turn of the century,
a county surveyor believed the original title descriptions to
be erroneous. Based solely on his affidavit-and without conducting
an on-the-ground survey-the U.S. patent office unilaterally amended
the title descriptions in 1901. The property involved in this
dispute, however, has recently become highly desirable for development.
Moreover, it was once part of the Nez Perce Indian Reservation.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Last December, Bureau of Indian
Affairs (BIA) issued Trespass Notices to eight Idaho residents.
Many more stand to lose the land which they have maintained and
paid taxes on for a half century, for the heirs to the original
members of the Nez Perce Tribe are claiming that the error in
the fee patent means that they own the land-not the people (and
their predecessors on interest) who have owned it since 1953.
BIA agrees and is intervening on behalf of the Indian heirs, asserting
that the present owners are trespassing on Indian land.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">If BIA succeeds in removing
the current occupants, the Indians whose interests the government
claims to represent will not retain title. The land has already
been sold to a developer. If BIA does not remove the current owners,
however, the Indian Law unit of the Legal Services Corporation-which
is representing the Indians free of charge-will sue BIA for failure
to protect the Indian heirs' rights.</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Defenders is asking Interior
Secretary Babbitt to exercise his discretion to amend the patents
to reflect the original and accurate 1873 descriptions, and the
actual use by all owners for an entire century.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Defenders Attempts to Stop <BR>
Wetlands Witch Hunt</B>
<P>
<font size=3>Defenders has filed a brief <I>amicus curiae</I>
on behalf of itself and two dozen grassroots property rights organizations
asking the U.S. District Court of Maryland to dismiss criminal
charges against James L.Wilson and his company, Interstate General.
This case bears a remarkable resemblance to the criminal prosecution
of Bill Ellen, a wetlands consultant who spent six months in a
federal penitentiary in 1992 for filling wetlands without a permit.
Now, the same prosecutor is gunning for Mr. Wilson. Defenders
is working with the defendant's private criminal counsel to have
the prosecution thrown out on a variety of grounds. Defenders
argued that the criminal charges brought for the filling of isolated
wetlands in this case are unconstitutional under the Fifth Amendment.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>One Day It's Billboards, the Next...Your House</B>
<P>
<font size=3>Defenders has filed a brief <I>amicus</I> <I>curiae</I>
in the U.S. Court of Appeals in the case of <I>Outdoor Graphics,
Inc. v. City of Burlington, Iowa</I>, arguing that a five-year
amortization period does not constitute &quot;just compensation&quot;
under the Fifth Amendment for the taking of private property.
At issue in this case is a 1988 city ordinance that outlawed the
construction of billboards within city limits. The city did not,
however, actually require Outdoor Graphics to take down its signs
until 1993. That grace (or &quot;amortization&quot;) period, the
city asserts, was the property owner's &quot;just compensation&quot;
for the destruction of the company's business.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: Defenders of Property
Rights, 6235 33rd St., NW, Washington, DC 20015, 202/686-4197,
fax 202/686-0240.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>INSTITUTE FOR JUSTICE</FONT></B>


<P>
<B>IJ Takes on Government Assault of Sanctity of the Home and
Right to Exclude</B>
<P>
<font size=3>The Institute for Justice has filed a lawsuit against
the Village of Park Forest (a suburb of Chicago), for allowing,
under its housing code, government inspectors to conduct warrantless
searches of single-family rental homes without tenant consent
or notice. The suit was filed on behalf of several Park Forest
tenants seeking to vindicate their private property rights under
the Fourth Amendment. The resulting decision from the case could
set a national precedent to bolster protection for the right of
property owners to exclude outsiders from their property. Government
inspectors, wishing to enter a tenant's home, will need to ask
for and receive either the explicit consent of tenants or, if
consent is denied, a search warrant based on some reasonable belief
that the housing code is being violated.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<b>Cleveland Becomes Second Battleground <BR>
for School Choice</b>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The Ohio Federation of Teachers
filed a suit to secure an injunction against the nation's second
school choice program, due to commence this Fall, in Cleveland.
The program provides, among other features, vouchers of approximately
$2,250 for about 1,500 low-income children in grades K-3 to attend
private schools. The program has attracted more than 50 schools
and 6,550 applicants-1,500 of whom were selected through a lottery
system. The lawsuit, styled <I>Gatton v. Goff</I>, challenges
the program on state and federal constitutional grounds. The primary
focus is establishment of religion. The Institute worked closely
with Governor Voinovich as the plan was developed, and having
worked in the Cleveland low-income community since last summer,
is preparing to intervene on behalf of Hope for Cleveland's Children,
the Hough Academy of Higher Learning, and individual families.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: Nina Shockraii, Director
of Outreach Programs, Institute for Justice, 1001 Pennsylvania
Ave., NW, Suite 200-S, Washington, DC  20004, 202/457-4240.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>NEW ENGLAND LEGAL FOUNDATION</FONT></B>


<P>
<B>Federal Circuit to Rehear <I>Preseault</I> Case</B>
<P>
<font size=3>In an unusual action, the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the Federal Circuit has vacated and will now rehear the <I>Preseault</I>
case. This overturns a recent decision by two judges of that court
who had held that Paul and Patricia Preseault had no remedy for
the United States' action in converting an abandoned railroad
right of way across their land into a heavily traveled public
recreational trail. The now-vacated decision had severely undercut
landowners' rights to seek compensation from the federal government
for &quot;taking&quot; their property. The court held that a party
was required to sue the government immediately after passage of
any law that &quot;foreshadowed&quot; a future taking. In the
Preseaults'<I> </I>case, that meant that they would have had to
sue in 1920, 60 years before the trail was even built. The new
decision breaths life back into over a dozen takings cases which
are following in the Preseaults' tracks. It is a major setback
for the government's effort to obtain rights over private land
without having to pay for those rights.</FONT>
<P>
<B>NELF to File <I>Amicus </I>Brief in <BR>
<B>Unemployment Case</B></B>
<P>
<font size=3>NELF will file a friend of the court brief for the
Connecticut Business and Industry Association in support of Yankee
Gas System's appeal of a decision ordering it to pay unemployment
benefits to striking workers.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The case involves a 1992 labor
dispute. Yankee offered workers a small raise and reserved the
right to change its medical insurance program in the future in
a manner the workers opposed. Negotiations broke down and workers
went on strike. During the strike the company kept operating,
using managers and some replacement workers. Three months later
the strike ended and the workers returned.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">A state agency has now characterized
the strike as a &quot;lockout&quot; and ordered Yankee to pay
unemployment benefits for the duration of the strike. The agency
found that the company's final offer was inferior to the prior
contract under which the workers were willing to keep working.
Both points are dubious. The new contract offered a modest raise
as well as the health insurance change, Furthermore, the agreement
to keep working was illusory since Yankee's workers reserved the
right to strike at any time they found more tactically convenient.
NELF's brief will focus on the decision's impact in shifting the
balance in labor disputes toward labor.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>NELF Represents Maine Oil Dealer</B>
<P>
<font size=3>NELF will represent Conrad Thibeault, a Maine fuel
dealer who voluntarily cleaned up some spilled oil on his property
and now is being made to pay for his good deed. When he discovered
the spill, Mr. Thibeault notified the state Departmnet of Enviromental
Protection, negotiated a cleanup plan and then actually cleaned
up the site. Only then did DEP tell Mr. Thibeault that it would
not reimburse him for 70% of the cleanup costs which it now felt
had gone to improving the property as well as cleaning it up.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Maine has an Oil Clean-up
Fund which is derived from fees paid by oil dealers like Mr. Thibeault.
The Fund was created to reimburse people for &quot;any expenses
involved&quot; in oil spill cleanups. The law contains not a word
about denying reimbursement if a cleanup also has the incidental
benefit of improving the property.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">NELF will appeal Mr. Thibeault's
case to the Fund Insurance Review Board and argue that when the
state approves the details of particular cleanup plans, it cannot
later renege and refuse to reimburse a person who in good faith
implemented the plan and cleaned up a spill. The state's policy
is shortsighted. It is not only unfair, but counterproductive.
If it becomes common practice, it will eliminate any incentive
for voluntary spill cleanups.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>NELF to Support Punitive Damages Appeal</B>
<P>
<font size=3>For decades it has been a common practice in the
telephone industry for field workers to carry their lunches to
the job site. Workers were given 30 minutes to eat lunch on the
site, but were not paid for that time.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The U.S. Labor Department
sued Southern New England Telecommunications, a Connecticut phone
company, claiming that its failure to pay workers for lunch breaks
violated the Fair Labor Standards Act. A federal judge agreed
and ordered the company to end the practice and to pay workers
over $4 million in back pay and overtime. The judge also held
that the violation was &quot;willful&quot; and therefore he doubled
the amount of damages to $9 million as a penalty<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">NELF will file an <I>amicus</I>
brief opposing the punitive double damages. The policy of not
providing paid lunches may not have been consistent with federal
law, but in light of the universal, decades-long practice in the
industry it cannot reasonably have been a &quot;willful&quot;
violation of the law. The U.S. Court of Appeals in New York will
hear the case.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: New England Legal
Foundation, 150 Lincoln St., Boston, MA 02111, 617/695-3660.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>PACIFIC LEGAL FOUNDATION</FONT></B>


<P>
<B>Washington Supreme Court Gives Lip Service to Landowner's Rights</B>
<P>
<font size=3>Despite the U.S. Supreme Court's unequivocal ruling
last June in <I>Dolan v. City of Tigard</I>, a Washington property
owner was unable to receive the benefits of that landmark decision
when the Washington Supreme Court applied <I>Dolan</I> in such
a manner as to render the precedent-setting decision meaningless.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Douglas County, Washington,
approved a 16-lot residential subdivision on the condition that
the owner dedicate various strips of land for future road widening.
Relying on the <I>Dolan </I>decision, the Court of Appeals found
the exaction to be an unconstitutional taking, since there was
no showing that the new homes would create any need to widen the
roads. The Washington Supreme Court thought otherwise.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Under <I>Dolan</I>, when government
requires the dedication of land in exchange for a permit, it must
<I>prove</I> that the particular land dedication at issue is &quot;roughly
proportional&quot; to any harm caused by the project being permitted.
Government has the burden of proof and must make an &quot;individualized
determination that the required dedication is related both in
nature and extent to the impact of the proposed development.&quot;
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">This case presented the first
opportunity for the Washington Supreme Court to consider this
&quot;rough proportionality&quot; test established in <I>Dolan</I>
and the type of information that is sufficient to justify an exaction
of land in return for a building permit. Unfortunately, the Washington
Supreme Court did not require any calculations of proportionality.
It simply upheld the land exactions based on the general increase
in traffic attributable to the development.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Fighting Government Extortion</B>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Ehrlich V. City of Culver City</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">.
Since 1992, PLF has been supporting Richard Ehrlich as <I>amicus
curia</I>e to help invalidate &quot;mitigation&quot; fees imposed
on him as a condition for receiving a permit to construct a housing
development.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">A ruling in favor of Mr. Ehrlich
could substantially limit local government's exactions of so-called
&quot;mitigation&quot; or &quot;linkage&quot; fees from private
development to finance unrelated public programs. PLF is striving
to achieve a ruling that conforms to the U.S. Supreme Court's
landmark decision in <I>Dolan v. City of Tigard</I>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">For several years, Mr. Ehrlich
operated a private tennis club but was unable to make a financial
success of it. In 1988, he closed the facility and donated most
of the movable equipment to the city and proposed a townhouse
condominium project on the property. The City Council approved
the project on condition that Mr. Ehrlich pay $280,000, which
the city estimated was the cost of building replacement tennis
courts.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">PLF contends that the fee
is unconstitutional because it fails the rough proportionality
test laid down in the <I>Dolan</I> case.  The <I>Ehrlich</I> case
differs in that the property owner is being asked to come up with
cash instead of land.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: Pacific Legal Foundation,
2151 River Plaza Dr., Suite 305, Sacramento, CA 95833, 916/641-8888,
fax 916/920-3444.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=4> The Rutherford Institute</font>
<P>
<B>Rutherford Asks Supreme Court to Hear &quot;Hot, Sexy and Safer&quot;
Case</B>
<P>
<font size=3>The Rutherford Institute is petitioning the Supreme
Court  to review a lawsuit on behalf of several parents and students
against the Chelmsford, MA, School Committee and Hot, Sexy and
Safer Productions.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The suit stems from two performances
given at Chelmsford High School in 1992 by Suzanne Landolphi of
Hot, Sexy and Safer Productions. Landolphi performed sexually
suggestive skits and gave sexually explicit monologues to students
in the ninth through twelfth grade. Landolphi's performance discussed
breast and penis size and advocated oral sex, masturbation and
homosexual activity among minors. In spite of the performance's
shockingly graphic nature, the school did not warn parents in
advance or provide for students to &quot;opt out.&quot;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The U.S. District Court previously
ruled in favor of the school and Hot, Sexy and Safer Productions,
a decision later affirmed by the First Circuit Court of Appeals.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: The Rutherford Institute,
P.O. Box 7482, Charlottesville, VA, 804/978-3888, Fax 804/978-1789,
e-mail rutherford@fni.com<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>SOUTHEASTERN LEGAL FOUNDATION</FONT></B>


<P>
<B>National Attention Focuses on Parental Rights Lawsuit</B>
<P>
<font size=3>SLF is proceeding with its parental rights lawsuit
in <I>Earles v. Stephens County School District, et. al., </I>which
is currently before the U.S. District Court. Filed on behalf of
the parents of two teenage sisters, the lawsuit challenges the
constitutionality of the school administration's actions in transporting
the minor girls during school hours to a local public health clinic,
where the girls received HIV/AIDS tests, PAP smear tests, condoms,
and prescription birth control pills-all without parental consent
or notification. The parents have been denied access to the results
of the tests.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">National media attention has
focused on this case as a lightning rod for the parental rights
debate in this country. SLF attorneys testified before a joint
U.S. House and Senate committee, which is considering proposed
parental rights legislation, on the constitutional status of the
parental right to direct and control the education and upbringing
of children. SLF attorneys pointed out that the U.S. Supreme Court
has established that parental rights are fundamental and, as such,
are entitled to the strongest legal protections against government
interference.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Business Owner Liability Gets Helping Hand</B>
<P>
<font size=3>In a victory for Georgia businesses and property
owners, the Georgia Supreme Court overturned a state Court of
Appeals decision, which held that property owners were charged
with constructive knowledge of criminal acts previously committed
on their property as part of their duty of ordinary care. The
Court of Appeals decision had made businesses liable for every
criminal act committed on their property, whether reasonably foreseeable
or not.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">In <I>Sun Trust Banks v. Killebrew</I>,
SLF argued as <I>amicus curiae</I> that any relaxation of the
doctrine of ordinary care would exacerbate the plight of those
property owners and businesses who are least able to protect their
own property, let alone their patrons. The Georgia Supreme Court
agreed, pointing out that imposing a greater burden on business
owners by the government is an abdication of its &quot;paramount&quot;
constitutional duty to &quot;protect person and property.&quot;
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Challenge to State's Intangibles Tax</B>
<P>
<font size=3>SLF is representing a Georgia corporation in a lawsuit
challenging Georgia's imposition of a tax on out-of-state intangible
personal property, including stocks and bonds, owned by Georgia
residents. The state currently collects about $40 million annually
from the tax, which is distributed to counties.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">At issue is the extent to
which the state can exempt the taxation of stocks and bonds of
Georgia corporations while it continues to tax the stocks and
bonds of out-of-state corporations. The U.S. Supreme Court is
currently considering a challenge to a similar tax in North Carolina,
which legal analysts believe will succeed. SLF attorneys point
out that Georgia's tax is a more egregious violation of the Commerce
Clause of the U.S. Constitution than the North Carolina tax. 
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: Southeastern Legal
Foundation, 3340 Peachtree Road, N.E., Suite 2515, Atlanta, Georgia,
30326, 404/365-8500, fax 404/363-0017.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>WASHINGTON LEGAL FOUNDATION</FONT></B>


<P>
<B>New Jersey Welfare Reform Defended</B>
<P>
<font size=3>WLF filed a brief in the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the Third Circuit supporting New Jersey's innovative welfare reform
program in <I>C.K. v. Shalala</I>, a suit brought by welfare recipients
who are represented by Legal Services of New Jersey, the ACLU
of New Jersey, and the NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund. Under
New Jersey's Aid to Families with Dependent Children system, a
single mother previously received an increase in her monthly cash
payment for each additional child born. New Jersey's reform program
eliminates the grant increase to mothers who have additional children
after joining the rolls. Seven AFDC recipients and their children
filed suit, alleging that the program violates the due process
and equal protection requirements of the United States and New
Jersey constitutions and that it violates federal statutes and
regulations governing AFDC, family planning services, and research
on human subjects. The case is before the Third Circuit following
the plaintiffs' appeal from their loss in the district court.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>EPA Sued Over Delinquent <BR>
Report to Congress</B>
<P>
<font size=3>On behalf of itself and nine Members of Congress,
WLF has sued the Environmental Protection Agency for failing to
provide Congress an economic analysis of the Clear Air Act. The
Clear Air Act of 1990 required the agency to file such a report
in November of 1991 and again in 1992 and 1994, but no report
has been filed-although businesses face civil and criminal penalties
if they fail to turn in timely reports to the EPA. The suit was
filed in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>EPA Petitioned To Protect <BR>
Business Civil Liberties</B>
<P>
<font size=3>As part of its Business Civil Liberties Project,
WLF has filed a petition for rulemaking with the EPA to require
that EPA personnel provide companies with a &quot;Statement of
Rights&quot; at the time of any inspection. The &quot;Statement
of Rights&quot; would advise companies that they have the right
to demand a search warrant, to consult with counsel, to accompany
inspectors and videotape them, and to receive &quot;split samples&quot;
of any effluent taken.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>22 Members of Congress Back California Challenge to &quot;Motor
Voter&quot;</B>
<P>
<font size=3>WLF filed a brief in the U.S. Supreme Court on behalf
of itself and 22 Members of the California delegation to Congress
supporting the state in its litigation over the constitutionality
of the federal &quot;motor voter&quot; law. In <I>Voting Rights
Coalition v. Wilson</I>, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth
Circuit had ruled against California's challenge to the law. In
its brief before the Supreme Court, WLF argues that the High Court
should hear the case and hold the statute unconstitutional.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Supreme Court Urged to Reject Discriminatory Enforcement Claim
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">WLF urged the U.S. Supreme
Court not to require prosecutors to explain themselves every time
the racial profile of those charged with a particular crime does
not match the racial profile of the population as a whole. In
a brief filed in <I>United States v. Armstrong</I>, WLF argued
that the Ninth Circuit had overstepped its authority in requiring
federal prosecutors to compile massive reports concerning its
crack cocaine enforcement efforts because blacks are disproportionately
charged with crack offenses. The Appeals Court had dismissed charges
against five defendants after the prosecutors refused to compile
the reports.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">CONTACT: Washington Legal
Foundation, 2009 Massachusetts Ave., NW, Washington, DC  20036,
202/588-0302, fax 202/588-0386.</FONT>
