<B><font size=3>Competitive Enterprise Institute Launches <BR>
Center for Private Conservation</FONT></B>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The Competitive Enterprise
Institute has launched the Center for Private Conservation, a
project aimed at improving public understanding of private sector
efforts to conserve environmental values. The Center will research
and document case studies of successful private efforts to conserve
resources and ecologically sensitive lands, and analyze how various
legal and social institutions can assist or hinder the ability
of private individuals and communities to advance environmental
ends.  CONTACT: Competitive Enterprise Institute, 1001 Connecticut
Ave., NW, Suite 1250, Washington, DC  20036, 202/331-1010, fax
202/331-0640.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Institute for Humane Studies to Sponsor Seminars</B>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">College Students are invited
to explore the tradition of personal freedom, free markets, and
liberty at free summer seminars sponsored by the Institute for
Humane Studies. Held at college campuses in the Washington, D.C.,
Philadelphia, Boston, St. Louis, Los Angeles, and San Francisco
areas, these week-long seminars allow for interaction with faculty
and the discussion and debate of ideas. The Institute is sponsoring
eight seminars throughout June and July. In addition to general
interdisciplinary seminars, some have a specific focus for students
interested in careers in academia, journalism, public policy,
film, or fiction. All seminars are free to accepted applicants.
Application deadline is April 15, 1996. CONTACT: Institute for
Humane Studies, George Mason University, 1-800-697-8799, e-mail
ihs@gmu.edu, Internet http://osfl.gmu.edu/~ihs.</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>The 18th Annual Publius Fellows Program</FONT></B>
<P>
<font size=3>The Publius Fellows Program is an intensive four-week
summer course in political philosophy designed for college seniors
and graduate students who are interested in writing for the public
prints. Now in its eighteenth year, the Publius Fellows Program
is dedicated to preserving the tradition of American political
writing. It aims to foster constructive commentary on the important
issues of today, informed and moderated by an understanding of
the philosophic and historical roots of American democracy. CONTACT:
Publius Fellows Program, The Claremont Institute, 250 West First
Street, Suite 330, Claremont, CA 91711, 909/621-6825, fax 909/626-8724.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>Visiting Scholars Programs at the University of Southern California</B>
<P>
<font size=3>The Visiting Scholar program at USC's Center for
International Studies is open to junior scholars</FONT><I>-</I><FONT SIZE=2>recent
PhD's and those who are at the very advanced stage of their dissertations</FONT><I>-</I><font size=3>who
are pursuing research on any aspect of international relations,
including international relations theory, foreign policy analysis,
security studies broadly defined, international political economy
or international history and law. The Pacific Council Visiting
Fellowship will support scholars at the junior, intermediate,
or senior level. For this Fellowship, the sponsors are especially
interested in candidates who are concerned with issues such as
trade, finance, industrial conversion, security, intellectual
property, immigration, and the relations of the U.S. with East
Asia, Canada, and Mexico.  CONTACT: Abraham Lowenthal, Director,
Center for International Studies, University of Southern California,
Social Science Building, Room B-1, Los Angeles, CA 90089-0035.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
